# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: borobudur-ship
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] For the first time, the Summer Asian Games were co-hosted by two regions; the Indonesian capital of Jakarta (which was hosting the Games for the first time since 1962), and Palembang, the capital of South Sumatra province.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Events were held in and around the two cities, including venues in Bandung and the provinces of West Java and Banten.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The opening and closing ceremonies of the Games were held at Gelora Bung Karno Stadium in Jakarta.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Games were originally awarded to Hanoi, Vietnam, but withdrew in 2014 due to budgetary concerns and other factors.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Several non-Olympic events were trimmed from the event programme, but several new disciplines being introduced at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo (including 3-on-3 basketball) were added.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Esports and canoe polo were also contested as demonstration sports.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] China led the medal tally for the tenth consecutive time.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] North and South Korea fielded a unified team during the opening ceremony and selected events, and also won their first-ever gold medal as a unified team at a multi-sport event.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] 6 world, 18 Asian and 86 Asian Games records were broken during the Games, while Japanese swimmer Rikako Ikee was announced as the most valuable player.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The OCA originally planned to hold these Games in 2019 rather than 2018, so that Asian Games would be held exactly a year before the 2020 Summer Olympics instead of the same year as the 2018 Winter Olympics.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] After they were awarded to Indonesia, the OCA backtracked on these plans and kept the Games in 2018, so that they would not interfere with the 2019 Indonesian general election.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Hanoi, Vietnam was originally selected to be the host after they won the bid against two other candidates, Surabaya and Dubai.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] They were awarded the winning bid on 8 November 2012, with 29 votes against Surabaya's 14 votes.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Dubai pulled out at the last minute, instead announcing their intention to focus on future bids.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The UAE's National Olympic Committee's vice-president denied any pullout and claimed that Dubai "did not apply for hosting 2019 Asian Games" and had "only considered" doing so.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] However, in March 2014, there were some concerns about Vietnam's ability to host.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] These included concerns over whether the anticipated budget of US$150 million was realistic.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] There were claims that the government would eventually spend over US$300 million.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] In addition, critics were concerned that several stadiums built in conjunction with the 2003 Southeast Asian Games had not been utilized since.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Former chairman of the Vietnam Olympic Committee Ha Quang Du also claimed that hosting the Asian Games would not boost tourism in Vietnam.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 17 April 2014, Vietnamese Prime Minister Nguyễn Tấn Dũng officially announced Hanoi's withdrawal from hosting, citing unpreparedness and economic recession as the main reasons for the withdrawal, saying "they have left the country unable to afford the construction of facilities and venues".
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Many Vietnamese people supported the decision to withdraw.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] No penalty was imposed for the withdrawal.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] After Hanoi's withdrawal, the OCA said that Indonesia, China, and the United Arab Emirates were major candidates under consideration to host.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Indonesia was widely regarded as a favourite, since Surabaya was the runner-up of the previous bid, and willing to do so if selected.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Philippines and India expressed their interest about hosting the Games, but India failed to submit a late bid because it was unable to get an audience with Prime Minister Narendra Modi after being given an extended deadline by the OCA.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 5 May 2014, the OCA visited several Indonesian cities, including Jakarta, Surabaya, Bandung, and Palembang.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] At this time Surabaya decided to drop their bid to host the Games and instead focus on hosting the already scheduled 2021 Asian Youth Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 25 July 2014, during a meeting in Kuwait City, the OCA appointed Jakarta as the host of the Games with Palembang as the supporting host.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] As the capital and the third biggest city on southern hemisphere, Jakarta was chosen because of its well-equipped sports facilities, adequate transportation networks, and other facilities such as hotels and lodging for guests.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 20 September 2014, Indonesia signed the host city contract, and was ceremonially appointed host during the closing ceremony of the 2014 Asian Games in Incheon.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] An organising committee was formed soon after the appointment.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] By 2015, the central government had allocated a budget of IDR 3 trillion (US$224 million) to prepare for the Games, with regional administrations also expected to supply some part of the funding.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] By July 2018, the budget allocation for the Games had been reported to be IDR 6.6 trillion (US$450 million) including IDR 869 billion (US$59 million) from sponsorships.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The total cost of arranging the Games is estimated about US$3.2 billion, of which $2.4 billion being spent on infrastructure development associated with the games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Phase 2 volunteering programme of Jakarta-Palembang 2018 Asian Games began on 18 December 2017 with target of 13,000 volunteers being set.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The volunteers wore clothing which included jacket, polo shirts and trousers which they collected from the Uniform Distribution and Accreditation Centre at the Sports and Recreation Arena in East Jakarta.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Volunteers also wore accreditation card which gain them access to specific venues and buildings around the site.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 10 May 2018, 100 days before their opening, the Asian Games torch was unveiled.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The design was inspired by the golok and skin — traditional weapons originating from Jakarta and Palembang.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The torch relay began at the Major Dhyan Chand National Stadium in New Delhi, host of the 1st Asian Games, on 15 July 2018.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The flame was generated from a parabolic mirror directed at the sun.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 18 July 2018, a ceremony took place in Brahma field by the 9th century Hindu temple of Prambanan near Yogyakarta, where the torch's flame from India were fused together with an Indonesian natural eternal flame taken from Mrapen, Central Java.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Subsequently, the Torch Relay Concert were performed marking the start of torch relay throughout the country.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The relay travelled through 54 cities in 18 provinces in Indonesia, including host cities.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The relay covered a total distance of 18,000 kilometres (11,000 mi).
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The relay finished on 17 August, the 73rd anniversary of the Proclamation of Indonesian Independence, at the National Monument in Jakarta before being carried into the opening ceremony at Gelora Bung Karno Stadium the next day.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The initial emblem for the 2018 Asian Games was first unveiled on 9 September 2015, in celebration of the country's National Sports Day.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 27 December 2015, the Games' mascot, Drawa, was unveiled by vice president Jusuf Kalla.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Both the emblem and mascot were a stylized rendition of the *cenderawasih*, a rare species of bird in Indonesia.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The designs were widely criticised for their outdated appearance, and Drawa in particular was criticised for having little connection to Indonesian culture and history (with some Indonesians joking that the mascot looked more like a chicken than a *cenderawasih*).
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 7 January 2016, Kalla announced that the original emblem and mascot had been withdrawn based on feedback, and that an open call for new designs would be held in partnership with the Creative Economy Agency.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Out of 60 submissions, the new emblem — entitled "Energy of Asia" — was unveiled on 28 July 2016.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The new emblem was modelled upon the Gelora Bung Karno Stadium, and was intended to symbolise unity among Asian countries.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Three new mascots were also unveiled: Bhin Bhin, a greater bird-of-paradise; Atung, a Bawean deer; and Kaka, a Javan rhinoceros.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] They represent the Eastern, Central, and Western regions of Indonesia, as well as strategy, speed and strength.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The mascots' outfits reflect traditional textiles; Bhin Bhin wears a vest with Asmat pattern details, Atung wears a *sarong* with *batik tumpal* patterns, and Kaka wears a Palembang *songket* with floral patterns.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Their names were derived from the national motto of Indonesia, *Bhinneka Tunggal Ika* (*Unity in Diversity*).
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The medal designs were unveiled in July 2018, featuring batik designs reflecting the unity and diversity of Indonesian and Asian culture.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On 18 August 2017, simultaneous events were held at Jakarta's National Monument and Palembang's Kuto Besak Fort to mark the one-year milestone before the Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The event in Jakarta was attended by president Joko Widodo, and featured performances by Taeyeon and Hyoyeon of K-pop group Girls' Generation.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Countdown clocks were unveiled at the Selamat Datang Monument and in front of Gelora Sriwijaya Stadium.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Several fun run events were held in Asian countries to promote the Games, beginning with Lahore, Pakistan in December 2017.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The games' merchandises and licensing products, which included mascot stuffed toys and other items, were sold in stores across Jakarta (including the Super Store at the Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex) from the end of 2017 to the end of September 2018.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The official theme song of the Games, "Meraih Bintang" ("Reach for the Stars"), was performed by Via Vallen.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The song was included in a larger official album for the Games, released on 13 July 2018 and featuring various Indonesian musicians.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] As part of an effort to appeal younger spectators, the Indonesian-Japanese idol group JKT48 was signed to perform at some of the Games' venues, such as jet ski, softball, and volleyball.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] They performed in select events between 19 August and 1 September in a group consisted of eight members from each of its teams.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] As part of creating a memorable and collectible item, the Indonesian postal service Pos Indonesia issued a philatelic collectible items of the 2018 Asian Games series.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] These items were issued on 18 January 2018 and 18 August 2018.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Games used a mix of new and existing venues in Jakarta and South Sumatra (with organizers aiming to reuse existing facilities and infrastructure, such as those built for the 2011 Southeast Asian Games, to help control costs), as well as Jakarta's neighbouring provinces of Banten, and West Java.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Venues were divided into four clusters, with three in Jakarta and its surrounding areas and one in Palembang.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Gelora Bung Karno Sports Complex in Jakarta hosted 13 events.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The 56-year-old Main Stadium was refurbished for the Games, replacing its existing bleachers and seating with an all-seater design (reducing its capacity to 77,193), and adding new sound systems and LED lighting among other enhancements.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Jakarta International Velodrome at Rawamangun in East Jakarta was rebuilt, at a cost of US$40 million for cycling, badminton, futsal, basketball, and wrestling.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The Jakarta International Equestrian Park at Pulomas underwent a US$30.8 million renovation, with a capacity of 1,000, 100 stables, lodging for athletes, and other amenities.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Jakabaring Sport City was used as an event site.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] While there were preliminary plans to increase the size of Gelora Sriwijaya Stadium from 36,000 to 60,000 seats, they were shelved.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The site still underwent some renovations, including also being converted from bleachers to an all-seater.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A new 40-lane bowling alley was constructed on the complex, as well as eight additional tennis courts.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The length of the canoeing and rowing venue in Jakabaring Lake was extended to 2,300 meters, while new rowing facilities and a tribune were built on the lake shore.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Other existing venues which was used for Games were also renovated, including Ranau Sports Hall as sepak takraw venue.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A 10-hectare athletes' village was constructed in Jakarta's Kemayoran district, with 7,424 apartments in 10 towers, and a total capacity of 22,272.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A second athletes' village was built at Jakabaring Sports City at Palembang, which housed 3,000 athletes and officials.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] As part of the Games preparation, the construction of the Jakarta MRT and Jakarta LRT was accelerated, though neither were ready for general commercial operation at the time of the opening ceremonies.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A line of Jakarta LRT connected the Velodrome at Rawamangun in East Jakarta to the Kelapa Gading district of North Jakarta, connecting the Velodrome with the Equestrian Park slightly to the north.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] City bus operator Transjakarta added 416 buses to serve the officials, and also provide free rides on selected days during the Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Palembang upgraded their transportation facilities ahead for the Games by building 25 kilometres of the Palembang Light Rail Transit from Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport to Jakabaring Sports City which opened for public use in July 2018.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Sultan Mahmud Badaruddin II International Airport is expanding its existing arrival and departure terminals to increase its capacity and also connecting the airport with the light rail transit (LRT) terminal by building a skybridge.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Other transportation facilities such as toll roads, flyovers, and bridges will be also built in and around the city.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The opening ceremony started at 19:00 Western Indonesian Time (UTC+7) on Saturday, 18 August 2018.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Wishnutama, then-CEO of Indonesian TV network NET. was the creative director for the ceremony.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The ceremony stage showcased a towering 26 meter-high mountain with a waterfall as its background, accompanied by Indonesian plants and flowers.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] North and South Korea delegates marched together under one unified flag of Korea, which marked the first time both countries did so in the Asian Games after 12 years.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The games was officially opened by the President of Indonesia, Joko Widodo.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] These changes reduced the total number of events to 431.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The final programme was unveiled in September 2017, increasing it to 462 events in 40 sports (61 disciplines) as the second-largest programme in Asian Games history.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Additional disciplines being introduced at the 2020 Summer Olympics were also added, including 3x3 basketball and BMX freestyle.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] For the first time in Asian Games history, esports and canoe polo were contested as demonstration sports in the Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Six video game titles, most notably Pro Evolution Soccer 2018, were featured in the esports events.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] All 45 members of the Olympic Council of Asia participated in the games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] North Korea and South Korea competed as a unified team in some events under the name "Korea" (COR), and marched together under the Korean Unification Flag during the opening and closing ceremonies.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] With a gold medal in the Women's 500 metre dragon boat competition, a unified team won their first-ever gold medal in a multi-sport event.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Originally set to compete as Independent Asian Athletes, the Kuwaitis were allowed to compete under their own flags just two days before the opening ceremony.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Below is a list of all the participating NOCs.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The number of competitors per delegation is indicated in brackets.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The closing ceremony started at 19:00 Western Indonesia Time (UTC+7) on Sunday, 2 September 2018 and ended at 21:25.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] In addition to local artists and a Chinese segment, the South Korean boybands Super Junior and iKon, and Indian singer Sidharth Slathia performed in the ceremony.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Mayor of Hangzhou Xu Liyi received the Games flag for the 2022 Games from Jakarta Governor Anies Baswedan and South Sumatra Governor Alex Noerdin.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] China led the medal table for the tenth consecutive time.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Korea claimed their first gold medal at the Games in the canoeing women's traditional boat race 500 m event.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A total of 37 NOCs won at least one medal, 29 NOCs won at least one gold medal and 9 NOCs failed to win any medal at the Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The top ten ranked NOCs at these Games are listed below.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] International Games Broadcast Services (IGBS), a joint venture between Host Broadcast Services (HBS) and IMG Media was appointed by the organiser in July 2017 to serve as the host broadcaster for these Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Involving 37 live production units, it distributed 2,400 hours of the Games content to its international rights holders.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] The International Broadcast Centre was constructed in Jakarta Convention Center, with a smaller one constructed at the Palembang cluster.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] On top of that, work in both host cities was delayed throughout 2015 because government funding was not immediately available.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Various concerns from traffic congestion problems, series of terror attacks, which local police claimed is a pre-Asian Games crackdown on terror suspects and petty street criminals, and already-provoked Indonesian fans at the venue.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Jakarta struggled with air pollution and river pollution problems.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] River pollution revealed where authorities covered a foul-smelling river near the athletes' village with black nylon mesh over fears it will be an eyesore at the showpiece event.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] Governor of Jakarta at that time, and the Indonesian Environment and Forestry Ministry quickly relieved the issues by various solutions.
[src:borobudur-ship/2018-asian-games] A doping case from a Turkmen wrestler was recorded, which jeopardize the sport's existence for future Games.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The **Admiralty Islands** are an archipelago group of 40 islands in the Bismarck Archipelago, to the north of New Guinea in the South Pacific Ocean.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] These are also sometimes known as the **Manus Islands**, after the largest island of the chain.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] These rainforest-covered islands constitute Manus Province, the smallest and least-populous province of Papua New Guinea, in its Islands Region.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The province had a population of 60,485 at the 2011 Census.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Many of the smaller Admiralty Islands are atolls and uninhabited.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The larger islands in the center of the group are Manus Island and Los Negros Island.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The other larger islands are Tong Island, Pak Island, Rambutyo Island and Lou Island to the east, Mbuke Island to the south and Bipi Island to the west of Manus Island.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Baluan Island, to the south of Manus Island, is the main island of the Pam Islands, where the Baluan-Pam language is spoken.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Other islands that have been noted as significant places in the history of Manus include Ndrova Island, Pityilu Island and Ponam Island.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The temperature of the Admiralty Islands varies little throughout the year, reaching daily highs of 30–32 °C (86–90 °F) and 20–24 °C (68–75 °F) at night.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Average annual rainfall is 3,382 mm (133 in) and is somewhat seasonal, with June–August being the wettest months.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Manus reaches an elevation of 700 m (2,300 ft) and is volcanic in origin and probably broke through the ocean's surface in the late Miocene, 8–10 million years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The substrate of the island is either directly volcanic or from uplifted coral limestone.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The main town in the islands is Lorengau on Manus, connected by road to an airport on nearby Los Negros Island, otherwise transport around the islands is by boat.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] There is little tourism, although the seas are attractive to divers, including Jean-Michel Cousteau who spent time on nearby Wuvulu Island in the 1970s.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Due to the isolated location, the rain forests of the Admiralty Islands are home to rare and endemic species of birds, bats and other animals, and are considered a separate ecoregion, the **Admiralty Islands lowland rain forests**.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The majority of the forests on Manus still remain, but some of the smaller islands have been cleared for coconut farming.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The typical tree species are various *Calophyllum* and *Sararanga* species.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The 58.5 km2 (22.6 sq mi) Ndrolowa Wildlife Management Area was created in March 1985 south of Lorengau on Manus Island and contains both terrestrial and marine regions.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] A further 240 km2 (93 sq mi) protected area has been established around the highest mountain on Manus, Mount Dremsel, but the level of protection remains undetermined in the UNEP World Database on Protected Areas.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Three of the bird species endemic to Admiralty Islands have been listed as vulnerable in the IUCN Red List: Manus fantail (*Rhipidura semirubra*), superb pitta (*Pitta superba*) and Manus masked owl (*Tyto manusi*), and the Manus dwarf kingfisher (*Ceyx dispar*) listed as near threatened.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Three other birds are endemic to Admiralty Islands but are classified as non-threatened or least concern: white-naped friarbird (*Philemon albitorques*), Manus monarch (*Monarcha infelix*) and Manus hawk owl (*Ninox meeki*).
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The islands are home to two endemic *Cornufer* frogs (*Cornufer admiraltiensis* and *Cornufer latro*) and four lizards, while the emerald green snail of Manus was the first terrestrial snail to be listed as vulnerable by the IUCN.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Along with New Guinea, the Bismarck Archipelago and the Solomon Islands Archipelago, the Admiralty Islands were first inhabited approximately 40,000 years ago, in the initial wave of migration out of Southeast Asia that also populated Australia.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] This early society appears to have cultivated taro, and to have deliberately introduced wild animals from New Guinea such as bandicoots and large rats.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Obsidian was gathered and traded throughout the Admiralty Islands archipelago.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The Lapita culture arose around 3,500 years ago, and its extent ranged from the Admiralty Islands to Tonga and Samoa.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Its origins are contested, but it may well have been a product of another wave of migration from Southeast Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Lapita society featured renowned pottery, stilt houses, the introduction of domestic animals such as pigs, dogs, and chickens, and substantial developments in agriculture and boat technology, allowing long-distance trade to develop.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Lapita society, as a distinct culture and extended trade network, collapsed around 2,000 years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The first European to visit the islands was the Spanish navigator Álvaro de Saavedra when trying to return from Tidore to New Spain in the summer of 1528.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Saavedra charted Manus as *Urays la Grande*.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Its visit was also reported in 1616 by the Dutch navigator Willem Schouten.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] The name 'Admiralty Islands' was devised by Captain Philip Carteret of the British Royal Navy in 1767.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Between 1884 and 1914 the area was administered as a German colony.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] In November 1914, the islands were occupied by troops of the Australian Naval and Military Expeditionary Force landed from the SS *Siar*.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] A few shots fired from a machine gun on *Siar* over the heads of the tiny German garrison at Lorengau were the last shots fired in the battle.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] After the war, the islands were governed by the Commonwealth of Australia under a League of Nations mandate.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Japanese troops landed on Manus Island on 7 April 1942.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] In 1944, Japanese forces occupying the islands were attacked and defeated by Allied forces in Operation Brewer.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Subsequently, a large American airbase and Manus Naval Base was built at Lombrum near Lorengau.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] Following Papuan independence in 1975, the Admiralty Islands became part of Papua New Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/admiralty-islands] They became the Manus Province of the Islands Region in Papua New Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] 1620), also known as the **Age of Exploration**, was part of the early modern period and overlapped with the Age of Sail.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was a period from approximately the 15th to the 17th century, during which seafarers from European countries explored, colonized, and conquered regions across the globe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery was a transformative period when previously isolated parts of the world became connected to form the world-system, and laid the groundwork for globalization.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The extensive overseas exploration, particularly the opening of maritime routes to the East Indies and European colonization of the Americas by the Spaniards and Portuguese, later joined by the English, French, and Dutch, spurred international global trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The interconnected global economy of the 21st century has its origins in the expansion of trade networks during this era.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The exploration created European colonial empires and marked an increased adoption of colonialism as a government policy in several European states.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] As such, it is sometimes synonymous with the first wave of European colonization.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This colonization reshaped power dynamics causing geopolitical shifts in Europe and creating new centers of power beyond Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portuguese oceanic exploration began with maritime expeditions to the Macaronesian islands, including the Canary Islands, as well as Madeira and the Azores.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It continued with voyages along the coast of West Africa in 1434, and culminated in the establishment of a sea route to India in 1498 by Vasco da Gama, which initiated Portugal's maritime and commercial presence in Kerala and the Indian Ocean.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spain also undertook other major early voyages, including the conquest of Mexico (1519–1521), the conquest of Peru (1532–1533), and the Manila galleon trade route (1565–1815), which linked the Americas and Asia across the Pacific.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European exploration initiated the Columbian exchange between the Old World (Europe, Asia, and Africa) and New World (Americas).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This exchange involved the transfer of plants, animals, human populations (including slaves), communicable diseases, and culture across the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Age of Discovery and European exploration involved mapping the world, shaping a new worldview and facilitating contact with distant civilizations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The continents drawn by European mapmakers developed from abstract "blobs" into the outlines more recognizable to us.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Simultaneously, the spread of new diseases, especially affecting American Indians, led to rapid declines in some populations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The era saw widespread enslavement, exploitation and military conquest of Indigenous peoples, concurrent with the growing economic influence and spread of Western culture, science, and technology leading to a faster-than-exponential population growth world-wide.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of discovery has been scrutinized, critically highlighting the history of the core term of this periodization.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The term "age of discovery" is in historical literature and still commonly used.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Something of which they had no prior knowledge had suddenly presented itself to their gaze." O'Gorman argues that the physical encounter with new territories was less important than the Europeans' effort to integrate this new knowledge into their worldview, what he calls "the invention of America".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Pagden examines the origins of the terms "discovery" and "invention".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In English, "discovery" and its forms in romance languages derive from "*disco-operio*, meaning to uncover, to reveal, to expose to the gaze", what was revealed existed previously.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Few Europeans during the period used the term "invention" for the European encounters, with the exception of Martin Waldseemüller, whose map first used the term "America".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A central legal concept of the discovery doctrine, expounded by the United States Supreme Court in 1823, draws on assertions of European powers' right to claim land during their explorations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The concept of "discovery" has been used to enforce colonial claiming and discovery, but has been challenged by Indigenous peoples and researchers.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Many indigenous peoples have fundamentally challenged the concept of colonial claiming of "discovery" over their lands and people, as forced and negating indigenous presence.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The period alternatively called the *Age of Exploration*, has been scrutinized through reflections on the exploration.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Its understanding and use, has been discussed as being framed and used for colonial ventures, discrimination and exploitation, by combining it with concepts such as the frontier (as in Frontier Thesis) and manifest destiny, up to the contemporary age of space exploration.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Alternatively, the term *contact*, as in first contact, has been used to shed more light on the age of discovery and colonialism, using the alternative names of *Age of Contact* or *Contact Period*, discussing it as an "unfinished, diverse project".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese began systematically exploring the Atlantic coast of Africa in 1418, under the sponsorship of Prince Henry the Navigator.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1488, Bartolomeu Dias reached the Indian Ocean by this route.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1492, the Catholic Monarchs of Spain funded Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus's (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) plan to sail west to reach the Indies, by crossing the Atlantic.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus encountered a continent uncharted by Europeans (though it had been explored and temporarily colonized by the Norse 500 years earlier).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later, it was called America after Amerigo Vespucci, a trader working for Portugal.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal quickly claimed those lands under the terms of the Treaty of Alcáçovas, but Castile was able to persuade the Pope, who was Castilian, to issue four papal bulls to divide the world into two regions of exploration, where each kingdom had exclusive rights to claim newly discovered lands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These were modified by the Treaty of Tordesillas, ratified by Pope Julius II.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1498, a Portuguese expedition commanded by Vasco da Gama reached India by sailing around Africa, opening up direct trade with Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Portuguese sailed further eastward, to the valuable Spice Islands in 1512, landing in China one year later.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Japan was reached by the Portuguese in 1543.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1513, Spanish explorer Vasco Núñez de Balboa crossed the Isthmus of Panama and reached the "other sea" from the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Thus, Europe first received news of the eastern and western Pacific within a one-year span around 1512.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] East and west exploration overlapped in 1522, when a Spanish expedition sailing westward, led by Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan (and, after his death in what is now the Philippines, by navigator Juan Sebastián Elcano), completed the first circumnavigation of the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spanish *conquistadors* explored the interior of the Americas, and some of the South Pacific islands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Their main objective was to disrupt Portuguese trade in the East.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1495, the French, English, and Dutch entered the race of exploration, after learning of Columbus' exploits, defying the Iberian monopoly on maritime trade by searching for new routes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first expedition was led by John Cabot in 1497 to the north, in the service of England, followed by French expeditions to South America and later to North America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later expeditions went to the Pacific Ocean around South America, and eventually by following the Portuguese around Africa, into the Indian Ocean; discovering Australia in 1606, New Zealand in 1642, and Hawaii in 1778.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 1580s to the 1640s, Russians explored and conquered almost the whole of Siberia, and claimed Alaska in the 1730s.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After the fall of the Western Roman Empire largely severed the connection between Europe and lands further east, Christian Europe was largely a backwater compared to the Muslim world, which conquered and incorporated large territories in the Middle East and North Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Christian Crusades to retake the Holy Land from the Muslims were not a military success, but they did bring Europe into contact with the Middle East and the valuable goods manufactured or traded there.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 12th century, the European economy was transformed by the interconnecting of river and sea trade routes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Economic growth of Iberia followed the Christian reconquest of Al-Andalus in what is now southern Spain and the siege of Lisbon (1147 AD), in Portugal.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The decline of the Fatimid Caliphate's naval strength, which started before the First Crusade, helped the maritime Italian states, mainly Venice, Genoa and Pisa, dominate trade in the Eastern Mediterranean, with merchants there becoming wealthy and politically influential.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Norman conquest of England, in the late 11th century, allowed for peaceful trade on the North Sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Hanseatic League, a confederation of merchant guilds and their towns in north Germany, along the North Sea and Baltic Sea, was instrumental in the commercial development of the region.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the 12th century, the regions of Flanders, Hainault, and Brabant produced the finest quality textiles in northwest Europe, which encouraged merchants from Genoa and Venice to sail there from the Mediterranean, through the Strait of Gibraltar, and up the Atlantic coast.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nicolòzzo Spinola made the first recorded direct voyage from Genoa to Flanders in 1277.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Technological advancements that were important to the Age of Exploration were the adoption of the magnetic compass and advances in ship design.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass was an addition to the ancient method of navigation based on sightings of the sun and stars.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was invented during the Chinese Han dynasty and had been used for navigation in China by the 11th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was adopted by Arab traders in the Indian Ocean.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass spread to Europe by the late 12th or early 13th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Use of the compass for navigation in the Indian Ocean was first mentioned in 1232.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first mention of use of the compass in Europe was in 1180.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Europeans used a "dry" compass, with a needle on a pivot.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The compass card was also a European invention.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The ships of the Age of Discovery post-dated the fusion of the northern European and Mediterranean shipbuilding traditions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to the late 13th/early 14th centuries, northern European ships were typically clinker built, with a single mast setting a square sail and a centre-line rudder hung on the sternpost with pintles and gudgeons.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Their counterparts in the Mediterranean were built with carvel hulls, had one or more masts (depending on size) which set lateen sails, and were steered with quarter-rudders positioned on the side of the hull.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Trade, pilgrimage and war brought ships from each tradition into the other's region, ultimately leading to the copying of features that were new to each.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Over the early 14th century, square sails started to be used in the Mediterranean, with the mainmast setting square rig and the mizzen carrying a lateen sail.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the first two decades of the 15th century this arrangement was copied in northern Europe where, by the late 1430s, some ships were built with carvel hulls.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The result of this merging of traditions was the full-rigged ship, a carvel hull with a sternpost-hung pintle-and-gudgeon rudder and three masts: the foremast and mainmast setting square sails and the mizzen a lateen sail.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Alongside this type of vessel, the caravel was used.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This type was also carvel built with a sternpost-hung rudder but could be completely lateen rigged or have some square sails.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Very few wrecks of Age of Discovery ships have been found and archaeologically investigated.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] More is known about Roman and Greek ships of classical antiquity than those of this period.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The caravel is particularly poorly understood, despite the number of "replicas" that have been constructed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] However, a particular set of hull construction characteristics have been identified from wrecks of this time, referred to as Iberian Atlantic shipbuilding tradition.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They are found in the Molasses Reef wreck, Highbourne Cay wreck, the Red Bay wreck and some sites in European waters.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European medieval knowledge about Asia beyond the reach of the Byzantine Empire was sourced in partial reports, often obscured by legends, dating back from the conquests of Alexander the Great and successors.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Another source was the Radhanite Jewish trade networks of merchants established as go-betweens between Europe and the Muslim world during the time of the Crusader states.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There were reports of great African Sahara, but the knowledge was limited for the Europeans, to the Mediterranean coast and little else, since the Arab blockade of North Africa precluded exploration inland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Knowledge about the Atlantic African coast was fragmented and derived mainly from old Greek and Roman maps based on Carthaginian knowledge, including Roman exploration of Mauritania.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Red Sea was barely known and only trade links with the maritime republics, Venice especially, fostered the collection of accurate maritime knowledge.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Indian Ocean trade routes were sailed by Arab traders.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] By 1400, a Latin translation of Ptolemy's *Geographia* reached Italy from Constantinople.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The rediscovery of Roman geographical knowledge was a revelation, both for map-making and worldview, although reinforcing the idea that the Indian Ocean was landlocked.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A prelude to the Age of Discovery was a series of European expeditions crossing Eurasia by land in the late Middle Ages.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongols had threatened Europe, but Mongol states also unified much of Eurasia and, from 1206 on, the *Pax Mongolica* allowed safe trade routes and communication lines from the Middle East to China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The close Italian links to the Levant raised curiosity and commercial interest in countries which lay further east.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There are a few accounts of merchants from North Africa and the Mediterranean, who traded in the Indian Ocean in late medieval times (see also Indo-Mediterranean § Medieval era).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Christian embassies were sent as far as Karakorum during the Mongol invasions of the Levant, from which they gained a greater understanding of the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The first of these travellers was Giovanni da Pian del Carpine, dispatched by Pope Innocent IV to the Great Khan, who journeyed to Mongolia and back from 1241 to 1247.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Russian prince Yaroslav of Vladimir, and his sons Alexander Nevsky and Andrey II of Vladimir, travelled to the Mongolian capital.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Though having strong political implications, their journeys left no detailed accounts.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Other travellers followed, like French André de Longjumeau and Flemish William of Rubruck, who reached China through Central Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Marco Polo, a Venetian merchant, dictated an account of journeys throughout Asia from 1271 to 1295, describing being a guest at the Yuan dynasty court of Kublai Khan in *Travels*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim fleet guarding the Strait of Gibraltar was defeated by Genoa in 1291.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In that year, the Genoese attempted their first Atlantic exploration when merchant brothers Vadino and Ugolino Vivaldi sailed from Genoa with two galleys, but disappeared off the Moroccan coast, feeding fears of oceanic travel.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1325 to 1354, a Moroccan scholar from Tangier, Ibn Battuta, journeyed through North Africa, the Sahara desert, West Africa, Southern Europe, Eastern Europe, the Horn of Africa, the Middle East, and Asia, having reached China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After returning, he dictated an account to a scholar he met in Granada, *The Rihla* ("The Journey"), the unheralded source on his adventures.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1357 and 1371, a book of supposed travels compiled by John Mandeville acquired popularity.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite the unreliable and often fantastical nature of its accounts, it was used as a reference for the East, Egypt, and the Levant in general, asserting the old belief that Jerusalem was the centre of the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the period of Timurid relations with Europe, in 1439, Niccolò de' Conti published an account of his travels as a Muslim merchant to India and Southeast Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1466–1472, Russian merchant Afanasy Nikitin of Tver travelled to India, which he described in his book *A Journey Beyond the Three Seas*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These overland journeys had little immediate effect.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Mongol Empire collapsed almost as quickly as it formed and soon the route to the east became more difficult and dangerous.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Black Death of the 14th century also blocked travel and trade for a time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Religion played a critical role in motivating European expansionism.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1487, Portuguese envoys Pero da Covilhã and Afonso de Paiva were sent on a covert mission to gather intelligence on a potential sea route to India and inquire about Prester John, a Nestorian patriarch and king, believed to rule over parts of the subcontinent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Covilhã was warmly received upon his arrival in Ethiopia, but forbidden from leaving.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] During the Middle Ages, the spread of Christianity throughout Europe fueled the desire to sermonise in lands beyond.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This evangelical effort became a significant part of the military conquests of European powers, like Portugal, Spain, and France, often leading to the conversion of indigenous peoples, voluntarily or forced.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Religious orders such as the Franciscans, Dominicans, Augustinians, and Jesuits partook in most missionary endeavours in the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] By the late 16th and 17th centuries, the latter's presence increased as they sought to reassert their power and revive the Catholic culture of Europe, which had been damaged by the Reformation.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Chinese had wide connections through trade in Asia and been sailing to Arabia, East Africa, and Egypt since the Tang dynasty (AD 618–907).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1405 and 1421, the third Ming emperor Yongle sponsored long range tributary missions in the Indian Ocean under the command of admiral Zheng He.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] A large fleet of new junk ships was prepared for the international diplomatic expeditions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The largest of these junks—that the Chinese termed *bao chuan* (treasure ships)—may have measured 121 metres (397 ft), and thousands of sailors were involved.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] At least seven well-documented expeditions were launched, each bigger and more expensive than the last.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleets visited Arabia, East Africa, India, Malay Archipelago, and Thailand (then called Siam), exchanging goods along the way.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They presented gifts of gold, silver, porcelain, and silk; in return, received such novelties as ostriches, zebras, camels, ivory, and giraffes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After the emperor's death, Zheng He led a final expedition departing from Nanking in 1431 and returning to Beijing in 1433.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It is likely this last expedition reached as far as Madagascar.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The travels were reported by Ma Huan, a Muslim voyager and translator who accompanied Zheng He on three of the expeditions, his account published as the *Yingya Shenglan* (Overall Survey of the Ocean's Shores) (1433).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages had a significant and lasting effect on the organization of a maritime network, using and creating nodes and conduits in its wake, thereby restructuring international and cross-cultural relationships and exchanges.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was especially impactful as no other polity had exerted naval dominance over all sectors of the Indian Ocean, prior to these voyages.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Ming promoted alternative nodes as a strategy to establish control over the network.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For instance, due to Chinese involvement, ports such as Malacca (in Southeast Asia), Cochin (Malabar Coast), and Malindi (Swahili Coast) had grown as key alternatives to other established ports.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The appearance of the Ming treasure fleet generated and intensified competition among contending polities and rivals, each seeking an alliance with the Ming.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expeditions developed into a maritime trade enterprise, with imperial control over local markets and court-monitored transactions, generating revenue for China and its partners.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They boosted regional trade and production, caused a supply shock in Eurasia and led to price spikes in Europe in the early 15th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The tributary relations promoted during the voyages manifested a trend toward cross-regional interconnections and early globalization in Asia and Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Diplomatic relations were built on mutually beneficial maritime trade and China's strong naval presence in foreign waters, with Chinese naval superiority being a key factor in these interactions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The voyages brought about the Western Ocean's regional integration and increase in international circulation of people, ideas, and goods.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It provided a platform for cosmopolitan discourses, which took place in locations such as the ships of the Ming treasure fleet, the Ming capitals of Nanjing as well as Beijing, and the banquet receptions organized by the Ming court for foreign representatives.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Diverse groups of people from maritime countries congregated, interacted, and traveled together as the treasure fleet sailed from and to China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first time, the maritime region from China to Africa was under the dominance of a single imperial power and allowed for the creation of a cosmopolitan space.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These long-distance journeys were not followed up, as the Ming dynasty retreated in the *haijin*, a policy of isolationism, having limited maritime trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the 8th until the 15th century, the Republic of Venice and neighboring maritime republics held the monopoly of European trade with the Middle East.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The silk and spice trade, involving spices, incense, herbs, drugs, and opium, made these Mediterranean city-states phenomenally rich.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Spices were among the most expensive and demanded products of the Middle Ages, as they were used in medieval medicine, religious rituals, cosmetics, perfumery, and food additives and preservatives.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They were imported from Asia and Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Muslim traders dominated maritime routes throughout the Indian Ocean, tapping source regions in the Far East and shipping for trading emporiums in India, mainly Calicut, westward to Hormuz in the Persian Gulf and Jeddah in the Red Sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From there, overland routes led to the Mediterranean.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Afterwards, the routes into Asia through the Black Sea and through Armenia and Persia became blocked by wars and banditry as the Mongol states disintegrated.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade route from the Persian Gulf to the Mediterranean by land is also dangerous due to the unstable territorial control of the Mamluk.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The trade from India went almost entirely into the Red Sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nevertheless, European spices have not become more expensive as a result.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Forced to reduce activity in the Black Sea, and at war with Venice, the Genoese had turned to North African trade of wheat, olive oil and a search for silver and gold.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans had a constant deficit in silver and gold, as it only went out, spent on eastern trade now cut off.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Several European mines were exhausted, The lack of bullion led to the development of a complex banking system to manage the risks in trade (the first state bank, *Banco di San Giorgio*, was founded in 1407 at Genoa).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing into the ports of Bruges and England, Genoese communities were then established in Portugal, who profited from their enterprise and financial expertise.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] European sailing had been primarily close to land cabotage, guided by portolan charts.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These charts specified proven ocean routes guided by coastal landmarks: sailors departed from a known point, followed a compass heading, and tried to identify their location by its landmarks.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For the first oceanic exploration Europeans used the compass, and advances in cartography and astronomy.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Arab navigational tools like the astrolabe and quadrant were used for celestial navigation.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Muslim lands in Asia were more economically developed, had better infrastructure, despite Europe's economic changes brought by the Black Death, allowing for more freedoms.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Islamic gunpowder empires concealed knowledge from European Christian traders about where lucrative locations such as Indonesia were.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1317, King Denis of Portugal made an agreement with Genoese merchant sailor Manuel Pessanha, appointing him first admiral of the Portuguese Navy, to defend the country against Muslim pirate raids.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Outbreaks of bubonic plague led to depopulation in the second half of the 14th century: only the sea offered alternatives, with most population settling in fishing and trading coastal areas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1325 and 1357, Afonso IV of Portugal encouraged maritime commerce and ordered the first explorations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Canary Islands, already known to the Genoese, were claimed as officially discovered under the patronage of the Portuguese, but in 1344, Castile disputed them.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] To ensure their trade monopoly, Europeans, beginning with the Portuguese, attempted to install a Mediterranean system of trade which used military intimidation, to divert trade through ports they controlled; there it could be taxed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1415, Ceuta, in North Africa, was conquered by the Portuguese aiming to control navigation of the African coast.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Young prince Henry the Navigator became aware of profit possibilities in the trans-Saharan trade routes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For centuries slave and gold trade routes linking West Africa with the Mediterranean passed over the Western Sahara Desert, controlled by the Moors.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He invested in sponsoring voyages down the coast of Mauritania, gathering merchants, shipowners and stakeholders interested in new sea lanes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the Atlantic islands of Madeira (1419) and the Azores (1427) were reached.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition leader who established settlements on Madeira, was explorer João Gonçalves Zarco.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Europeans did not know what lay beyond Cape Non (Cape Chaunar) on the African coast, and whether it was possible to return once crossed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Nautical myths warned of monsters or an edge of the world, but Henry's navigation challenged such beliefs: starting in 1421, systematic sailing overcame it, reaching the difficult Cape Bojador that in 1434 one of Henry's captains, Gil Eanes, finally passed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1440, caravels were extensively used for the exploration of the coast of Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This was an Iberian ship type, used for fishing, commerce and military purposes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It had a sternpost-mounted rudder, a shallow draft helpful in exploring coastlines, a good sailing performance, with a windward ability.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The lateen rig was less useful when sailing downwind – which explains Christopher Columbus (Italian: *Cristoforo Colombo*) re-rigging the *Niña* with square rig.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] For celestial navigation the Portuguese used the ephemerides, which experienced a remarkable diffusion in the 15th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These were astronomical charts plotting the location of the stars.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Published in 1496 by Jewish astronomer and mathematician Abraham Zacuto, the Almanac Perpetuum included some of these tables for the movements of stars.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] These revolutionized navigation, allowing the calculation of latitude.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Exact longitude remained elusive from mariners for centuries.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Using the caravel, systematic exploration continued southerly, advancing one degree a year.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Senegal and Cape Verde Peninsula were reached in 1445 and in 1446, Álvaro Fernandes pushed on almost as far as present-day Sierra Leone.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1453, the fall of Constantinople to the Ottomans was a perceived blow to Christendom and established business links with the East.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The king, who had been inquiring of Genoese experts about a seaway to India, commissioned the Fra Mauro world map, which arrived in Lisbon in 1459.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1456, Diogo Gomes reached the Cape Verde archipelago.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In the next decade captains at the service of Prince Henry, discovered the remaining islands which were occupied during the 15th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Gulf of Guinea was reached in the 1460s.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1460, Pedro de Sintra reached Sierra Leone.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prince Henry died in November after which, given the meagre revenues, exploration was granted to Lisbon merchant Fernão Gomes in 1469, who in exchange for the monopoly of trade in the Gulf of Guinea had to explore 100 miles (161 kilometres) each year for five years.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] With his sponsorship, explorers João de Santarém, Pedro Escobar, Lopo Gonçalves, Fernão do Pó, and Pedro de Sintra made it beyond those goals.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They reached the Southern Hemisphere and islands of the Gulf of Guinea, including São Tomé and Príncipe and Elmina in 1471.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] There, in what came to be called the "Gold Coast", in today's Ghana, a thriving alluvial gold trade was found among the natives, Arab and Berber traders.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1478, during the War of the Castilian Succession, near the coast at Elmina a large battle was fought between a Castilian armada of 35 caravels, and a Portuguese fleet for the hegemony of the Guinea trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The war ended with a Portuguese victory, followed by official recognition by the Catholic Monarchs of Portuguese sovereignty over most of the disputed West African territories embodied in the Treaty of Alcáçovas, 1479.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1481, João II decided to build São Jorge da Mina factory.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1482, the Congo River was explored by Diogo Cão, who in 1486 continued to Cape Cross (modern Namibia).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The next crucial breakthrough was in 1488, when Bartolomeu Dias rounded the southern tip of Africa, which he named Cabo das Tormentas, "Cape of Storms", then sailing east as far as the mouth of the Great Fish River, proving the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Pero da Covilhã, sent out travelling secretly overland, had reached Ethiopia having collected important information about the Red Sea and Quenia coast, suggesting a sea route to the Indies would soon be forthcoming.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Soon the cape was renamed by King John II of Portugal the *Cape of Good Hope*, because of the optimism engendered by the possibility of a sea route to India, proving false the view that had existed since Ptolemy that the Indian Ocean was land-locked.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Based on later stories of the phantom island known as Bacalao and the carvings on Dighton Rock some have speculated that Portuguese explorer João Vaz Corte-Real discovered Newfoundland in 1473, but the sources are considered unreliable.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal's Iberian rival, Castile, had begun to establish its rule over the Canary Islands in 1402, but became distracted by internal Iberian politics and the repelling of Islamic invasion attempts through most of the 15th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Following the unification of the crowns of Castile and Aragon, an emerging modern Spain became committed to the search for new trade routes overseas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Crown of Aragon had been an important maritime power, controlling territories in eastern Spain, southwestern France, major islands like Sicily, Malta, and the Kingdom of Naples and Sardinia, with mainland possessions as far as Greece.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1485 and 1488, Columbus had presented the project to king John II of Portugal, who rejected it.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 3 August 1492, Columbus departed from Palos de la Frontera.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Land was sighted on 12 October, and Columbus called the island *San Salvador* (Guanahani now in The Bahamas), in what he thought to be the East Indies.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus explored the north coast of Cuba and Hispaniola, by 5 December.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He was received by the native cacique Guacanagari, who gave him permission to leave some men behind.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus left 39 and founded the settlement of *La Navidad* in what is now Haiti.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Before returning to Spain, he kidnapped 10-25 natives.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Only 7-8 of the 'Indians' arrived alive, but they made an impression on Seville.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 15 March 1493, he arrived in Barcelona, where he reported to Isabella and Ferdinand.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Word of his discovery of new lands spread throughout Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Columbus and other Spanish explorers were initially disappointed with their discoveries—unlike Africa or Asia, the Caribbean islanders had little to trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The islands thus became the focus of colonization efforts.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was not until the continent was explored that Spain found the wealth it had sought.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Shortly after Columbus's return from what would be called the "West Indies", a division of influence became necessary to avoid conflict between the Spaniards and Portuguese.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It did not mention Portugal, which could not claim newly discovered lands east of the line.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] King John II of Portugal was displeased with the arrangement, feeling it gave him too little land—preventing him from reaching India, his goal.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He negotiated directly with Ferdinand and Isabella to move the line west, allowing him to claim newly discovered lands east of it.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1494, the Treaty of Tordesillas divided the world between Portugal and Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Portugal gained control over Africa, Asia, and eastern South America (Brazil), encompassing everything outside Europe east of a line drawn 370 leagues west of the Cape Verde islands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Spaniards received everything west of this line, including the islands discovered by Columbus on his first voyage.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The dividing line, situated about halfway between Portuguese Cape Verde and Spanish discoveries in the Caribbean, split the known world of Atlantic islands evenly.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1500, Pedro Álvares Cabral, initially considering the Brazilian coast as a large island, claimed it for Portugal east of the dividing line.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This claim was acknowledged by the Spaniards.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral, heading towards India, followed a corridor in the Atlantic negotiated by the treaty for favorable winds.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Later the Spanish territory would prove to include huge areas of the continental mainland of North and South America, though Portuguese-controlled Brazil would expand across the line, and settlements by other European powers ignored the treaty.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Little of the divided area had actually been seen by Europeans, as it was only divided by a geographical definition rather than control on the ground.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The desire to compete with the Ottoman Empire and Columbus's first voyage spurred further maritime exploration and, from 1497, other explorers headed west.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] That year John Cabot (Italian: *Giovanni Caboto*), also a commissioned Italian, got letters patent from King Henry VII of England.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Sailing from Bristol Cabot crossed the Atlantic from a northerly latitude hoping the voyage to the "West Indies" would be shorter and made landfall in North America, possibly Newfoundland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Prior to Cabot's voyage, the furthest European expeditions in the North Atlantic had been by Norse explorers, who established settlements in Newfoundland and Greenland, which were abandoned in the 11th century and mid-15th century, respectively.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Merchants from Bristol had sponsored exploratory voyages in the 1480s, which did not report anything of note.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1499, João Fernandes Lavrador was licensed by the King of Portugal and together with Pero de Barcelos they first sighted Labrador, which was granted and named after him.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Between 1499 and 1502, the brothers Gaspar and Miguel Corte Real explored and named the coasts of Greenland and Newfoundland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Both explorations are noted in the 1502 Cantino planisphere.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1497, newly crowned King Manuel I of Portugal sent an exploratory fleet eastwards, fulfilling his predecessor's project of finding a route to the Indies.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In July 1499, news spread that the Portuguese had reached the "true Indies", as a letter was dispatched by the Portuguese king to the Spanish Monarchs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The third expedition by Columbus in 1498 was the beginning of the first successful Spanish colonization in the West Indies, on the island of Hispaniola.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Despite growing doubts, Columbus refused to accept he had not reached the Indies.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He discovered the mouth of the Orinoco River on the north coast of South America and thought the huge quantity of fresh water coming from it could only be from a continental land mass, which he was certain was Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] As shipping between Seville and the West Indies grew, knowledge of the Caribbean islands, Central America and the northern coast of South America increased.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] One of these Spanish fleets, that of Alonso de Ojeda and Amerigo Vespucci in 1499–1500 reached land at the coast of what is now Guyana, where the two seem to have separated in opposite directions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci sailed southward, discovering the mouth of the Amazon River in July 1499, and reaching 6°S, in present-day north east Brazil, before turning around.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vicente Yáñez Pinzon was blown off course and reached what is now the northeast coast of Brazil on 26 January 1500, exploring as far south as the present-day state of Pernambuco.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] His fleet was the first to fully enter the Amazon River estuary, which he named *Saint Mary's River of the Freshwater Sea*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The land was too far east for the Castilians to claim under the Treaty of Tordesillas, but the discovery created Castilian interest, with a second voyage by Pinzon in 1508 (the Pinzón–Solís voyage) and a voyage in 1515–1516 by a navigator of the 1508 expedition, Juan Díaz de Solís.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The 1515–1516 expedition was spurred on by reports of Portuguese exploration of the region.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It ended when de Solís and some of his crew disappeared when exploring the River Plata in a boat, but what they found reignited Spanish interest, and colonization began in 1531.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In April 1500, the second Portuguese India Armada, headed by Pedro Álvares Cabral, with a crew of expert captains, encountered the Brazilian coast as it swung westward in the Atlantic while performing a large volta do mar to avoid becalming in the Gulf of Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 21 April, a mountain was seen and named *Monte Pascoal*, and on 22 April Cabral landed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] On 25 April, the entire fleet sailed into the harbour they named *Porto Seguro*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral perceived that the new land lay east of the line of Tordesillas, and sent an envoy to Portugal with the discovery in letters, including the letter of Pero Vaz de Caminha.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Believing the land to be an island, he named it Ilha de Vera Cruz.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From the east coast, the fleet then turned eastward towards the southern tip of Africa and India.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Cabral was the first captain to touch four continents, leading the first expedition that connected and united Europe, Africa, the New World, and Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] At the invitation of King Manuel I of Portugal, Amerigo Vespucci participated as an observer in the exploratory voyages to the east coast of South America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] It was understood that Columbus had not reached Asia but found a new continent, the Americas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The Americas were named in 1507 by cartographers Martin Waldseemüller and Matthias Ringmann, after Amerigo Vespucci.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1501 to 1502, one of these Portuguese expeditions, led by Gonçalo Coelho, sailed south along the coast of South America to the bay of present-day Rio de Janeiro.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci's account states that the expedition reached the latitude "South Pole elevation 52° S", in the "cold" latitudes of what is now southern Patagonia, before turning back.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Vespucci wrote that they headed toward the southwest and south, following "a long, unbending coastline", apparently coincident with the southern South American coast.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] This seems controversial, since he changed part of his description in the subsequent letter, stating a shift, from about 32° S (Southern Brazil) to the south-southeast, to open sea, maintaining that they reached 50°/52° S.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1503, Binot Paulmier de Gonneville, challenging the Portuguese policy of *mare clausum*, led one of the earliest French Normand and Breton expeditions to Brazil.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] He intended to sail to the East Indies, but near the Cape of Good Hope, his ship was diverted to the west by a storm, and landed in the present-day state of Santa Catarina (southern Brazil), on 5 January 1504.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1511 to 1512, Portuguese captains João de Lisboa and Estevão de Fróis reached the River Plata estuary in present-day Uruguay and Argentina, and went as far south as the present-day Gulf of San Matias at 42°S.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The expedition reached a cape extending north to south which they called Cape of "Santa Maria" (Punta del Este); and after 40°S they found a "Cape" or "a point or place extending into the sea", and a "Gulf".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] After they had navigated for nearly 300 km (186 mi) to round the cape, they again sighted the continent on the other side and steered towards the northwest, but a storm prevented them from making headway.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Driven away by the *Tramontane* or north wind, they retraced their course.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] Christopher de Haro, a Fleming of Sephardic origin, who would serve the Spanish Crown after 1516, believed the navigators had discovered a southern *strait* to west and Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] In 1519, an expedition sent by the Spanish Crown to find a way to Asia was led by the experienced Portuguese navigator Ferdinand Magellan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] The fleet explored the rivers and bays as it charted the South American coast, until it found a way to the Pacific Ocean through the Strait of Magellan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] From 1524 to 1525, Aleixo Garcia, a Portuguese conquistador, led a private expedition of shipwrecked Castilian and Portuguese adventurers, who recruited about 2,000 Guaraní Indians.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They explored the territories of present-day southern Brazil, Paraguay, and Bolivia, using the native trail network, the *Peabiru*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p01] They were the first Europeans to cross the Chaco and reach the outer territories of the Inca Empire on the hills of the Andes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Protected from direct Spanish competition by the Treaty of Tordesillas, Portuguese eastward exploration and colonization continued apace.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Twice, in 1485 and 1488, Portugal officially rejected Genoese Christopher Columbus's idea of reaching India by sailing westwards.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] King John II of Portugal's experts rejected it, for they held the opinion that Columbus's estimation of a travel distance of 2,400 miles (3,860 km) was low, and in part because Bartolomeu Dias departed in 1487 trying the rounding of the southern tip of Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They believed that sailing east would require a far shorter journey.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dias's return from the Cape of Good Hope in 1488, and Pero da Covilhã's travel to Ethiopia overland indicated that the richness of the Indian Ocean was accessible from the Atlantic.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In July 1497, a small exploratory fleet of four ships and about 170 men left Lisbon under the command of Vasco da Gama.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] By December the fleet passed the Great Fish River—where Dias had turned back—and sailed into waters unknown to the Europeans.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Sailing into the Indian Ocean, da Gama entered a maritime region that had three different and well-developed trade circuits.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The one da Gama encountered connected Mogadishu on the east coast of Africa; Aden, at the tip of the Arabian peninsula; the Persian port of Hormuz; Cambay, in northwestern India; and Calicut, in southwestern India.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 20 May 1498, they arrived at Calicut.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The efforts of Vasco da Gama to get favorable trading conditions were hampered by the low value of their goods, compared with the valuable goods traded there.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years and two days after departure, Gama and a survivor crew of 55 men returned in glory to Portugal as the first ships to sail directly from Europe to India.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Da Gama's voyage is romanticized in the Os Lusíadas, an epic poem by fellow discovery-era traveler Luís de Camões.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The poem is widely regarded as Portugal's greatest literary achievement.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1500, a second, larger fleet of thirteen ships and about 1500 men were sent to India.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Under the command of Pedro Álvares Cabral, they made the first landfall on the Brazilian coast, giving Portugal its claim.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Later, in the Indian Ocean, one of Cabral's ships reached Madagascar (1501), which was partly explored by Tristão da Cunha in 1507; Mauritius was discovered in 1507, Socotra occupied in 1506.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Lourenço de Almeida landed in Sri Lanka, the eastern island named "Taprobane" in remote accounts of Alexander the Great's and 4th-century BC Greek geographer Megasthenes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On the Asiatic mainland, the first factories (trading-posts) were established at Kochi and Calicut (1501) and then Goa (1510).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Portuguese continued sailing eastward from India, entering a second existing circuit of the Indian Ocean trade, from Calicut and Quillon in India, to Southeast Asia, including Malacca and Palembang.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1511, Afonso de Albuquerque conquered Malacca for Portugal, then the center of Asian trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] East of Malacca, Albuquerque sent several diplomatic missions: Duarte Fernandes as the first European envoy to the Kingdom of Siam (modern Thailand).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Learning the location of the so-called "spice islands", heretofore a secret from the Europeans, were the Spice Islands, mainly the Banda, then the world's only source of nutmeg and cloves.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Reaching these was the main purpose for the Portuguese voyages in the Indian Ocean.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Albuquerque sent an expedition led by António de Abreu to Banda (via Java and the Lesser Sunda Islands), where they were the first Europeans to arrive in early 1512, after taking a route through which they also reached first the islands of Buru, Ambon, and Seram.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In May 1513, Jorge Álvares, one of the Portuguese envoys, reached China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Fernão Pires de Andrade visited Canton in 1517 and opened up trade with China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After a few decades, hostilities between the Portuguese and Chinese ceased and in 1557 the Chinese allowed the Portuguese to occupy Macau.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To enforce a trade monopoly, Muscat and Hormuz in the Persian Gulf were seized by Afonso de Albuquerque in 1507 and in 1515, respectively.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He also entered into diplomatic relations with Persia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, while trying to conquer Aden, an expedition led by Albuquerque cruised the Red Sea inside the Bab al-Mandab and sheltered at Kamaran island.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1521, a force under António Correia conquered Bahrain, ushering in a period of almost 80 years of Portuguese rule of the Gulf archipelago.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Red Sea, Massawa was the most northerly point frequented by the Portuguese until 1541, when a fleet under Estevão da Gama penetrated as far as Suez.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1513, about 40 miles (64 kilometres) south of Acandí, in present-day Colombia, Spanish Vasco Núñez de Balboa heard unexpected news of an "other sea" rich in gold, which he received with great interest.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With few resources and using information given by *caciques*, he journeyed across the Isthmus of Panama with 190 Spaniards, a few native guides, and a pack of dogs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Balboa, using a brigantine and ten native canoe, explored the coast, facing battles and dense jungles.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 25 September, after crossing the Chucunaque River mountains, he became the first European to see the Pacific Ocean from the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition briefly navigated the Pacific, naming the bay *San Miguel* and the sea *Mar del Sur* (South Sea).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Seeking gold, Balboa traversed cacique lands to the islands, naming the largest Isla Rica (now Isla del Rey) and the group *Archipiélago de las Perlas*, names still in use today.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1515 to 1516, the Spanish fleet led by Juan Díaz de Solís sailed down the east coast of South America as far as Río de la Plata, which Solís named shortly before he died while trying to find a passage to the "South Sea".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] By 1516, several Portuguese navigators conflicting with King Manuel I of Portugal gathered in Seville to serve the newly crowned Charles I of Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Among them were explorers Diogo and Duarte Barbosa, Estêvão Gomes, João Serrão, and Ferdinand Magellan, cartographers Jorge Reinel and Diogo Ribeiro, cosmographers Francisco and Ruy Faleiro and the Flemish merchant Christopher de Haro.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Ferdinand Magellan had sailed in India for Portugal up to 1513, when the Spice Islands were reached, and had kept contact with Francisco Serrão who was living there.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Magellan developed the theory that the Spice Islands were in the Tordesillas Spanish area, based on studies by Faleiro brothers.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Aware of the efforts of the Spanish to find a route to India by sailing west, Magellan presented his plan to Charles I of Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The king and Christopher de Haro financed Magellan's expedition.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A fleet was put together, and Spanish navigators such as Juan Sebastián Elcano joined the enterprise.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 10 August 1519, they departed from Seville with a fleet of five ships—the caravel flagship *Trinidad* under Magellan's command, and carracks *San Antonio*, *Concepcion*, *Santiago* and *Victoria*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They contained a crew of about 237 European men from several regions, with the goal of reaching the Spice Islands by travelling west, trying to reclaim it under Spain's economic and political sphere.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet sailed south, avoiding Portuguese Brazil, and became the first to reach Tierra del Fuego.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Starting on 21 October, they navigated the 373-mile (600 km) Strait of Magellan, entering the Pacific on 28 November, which Magellan named Mar Pacífico for its calm waters.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After crossing the Pacific, Magellan was killed in the Battle of Mactan in the Philippines.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Sebastián Elcano completed the voyage, reaching the Spice Islands in 1521.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 6 September 1522, the *Victoria* returned to Spain, completing the first circumnavigation of the globe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Of the original crew, only 18 men completed the circumnavigation; 17 returned later, including twelve captured by the Portuguese and five survivors of the Trinidad.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Antonio Pigafetta, a Venetian scholar, kept a detailed journal that is a key source of information about the voyage.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This round-the-world voyage gave Spain valuable knowledge of the world and its oceans which later helped in the exploration and settlement of the Philippines.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Soon after Magellan's expedition, the Portuguese rushed to seize the surviving crew and built a fort in Ternate.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1525, Charles I of Spain sent another expedition westward to colonize the Spice Islands, claiming that they were in his zone of the Treaty of Tordesillas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The fleet of seven ships and 450 men was led by García Jofre de Loaísa and included the most notable Spanish navigators: Juan Sebastián Elcano and Loaísa, who died then, and the young Andrés de Urdaneta.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Near the Strait of Magellan one of the ships was pushed south by a storm, reaching 56° S, where they thought seeing "*earth's end*": so Cape Horn was crossed for the first time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition reached the islands with great difficulty, docking at Tidore.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The conflict with the Portuguese established in nearby Ternate was inevitable, starting nearly a decade of skirmishes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As there was not a set eastern limit to the Tordesillas line, both kingdoms organized meetings to resolve the issue.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1524 to 1529, Portuguese and Spanish experts met at Badajoz-Elvas trying to find the exact location of the antimeridian of Tordesillas, which would divide the world into two equal hemispheres.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Each crown appointed three astronomers and cartographers, three pilots, and three mathematicians.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Lopo Homem, Portuguese cartographer and cosmographer was on the board, along with cartographer Diogo Ribeiro of the Spanish delegation.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The board met several times without reaching an agreement: the knowledge at that time was insufficient for an accurate calculation of longitude, and each group gave the islands to its sovereign.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The issue was settled only in 1529, after a long negotiation, with the signing of Treaty of Zaragoza, which allocated the Spice Islands to Portugal and the Philippines to Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1525 to 1528, Portugal sent several expeditions around the Spice Islands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Gomes de Sequeira and Diogo da Rocha were sent north by the governor of Ternate Jorge de Menezes, being the first Europeans to reach the Caroline Islands, which they named *Islands of Gomes de Sequeira*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1526, Jorge de Meneses docked on Biak and Waigeo islands, Papua New Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Based on these explorations stands the theory of Portuguese discovery of Australia, one among several competing theories about the early discovery of Australia, supported by Australian historian Kenneth McIntyre, stating it was discovered by Cristóvão de Mendonça and Gomes de Sequeira.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1527, Hernán Cortés fitted out a fleet to find new lands in the "South Sea" (Pacific Ocean), asking his cousin Álvaro de Saavedra Cerón to take charge.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 31 October 1527, Saavedra sailed from New Spain, crossing the Pacific and touring the north of New Guinea, then named *Isla de Oro*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In October 1528, one of the vessels reached the Spice Islands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In his attempt to return to New Spain he was diverted by the northeast trade winds, which threw him back, so he tried sailing back down, to the south.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He returned to New Guinea and sailed northeast, where he sighted the Marshall Islands and the Admiralty Islands, but again was surprised by the winds, which brought him a third time to the Moluccas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This westbound return route was hard to find but was eventually discovered by Andrés de Urdaneta in 1565.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Rumors of undiscovered islands northwest of Hispaniola reached Spain by 1511, ushering King Ferdinand's interest in forestalling further exploration.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] While the Portuguese were making huge gains in the Indian Ocean, the Spanish invested in exploring inland in search of gold and other valuable resources.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The members of these expeditions, the conquistadors, were not soldiers in an army, but more like soldiers of fortune; they came from a variety of backgrounds including artisans, merchants, clergy, lawyers, lesser nobility and a few freed slaves.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually supplied their own equipment or were extended credit to purchase it in exchange for a share in profits.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They usually had no professional military training, but a number of them had previous experience on other expeditions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the Americas, the Spanish encountered large indigenous empires and formed alliances with indigenous people through small expeditions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After establishing Spanish sovereignty and discovering wealth, the crown focused on implementing Spanish state and church institutions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A key element was the 'spiritual conquest' through Christian evangelization.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The initial economy relied on a tribute and forced labor under the *encomienda* system.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The discovery of vast silver deposits transformed both the colonial economies of Mexico and Peru and Spain's economy.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With global trade networks and valuable American crops, Spain's economy strengthened, enhancing its status as a world power.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] During this time, pandemics of European diseases such as smallpox decimated the indigenous populations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1512, to reward Juan Ponce de León for exploring Puerto Rico in 1508, King Ferdinand urged him to seek these new lands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He would become governor of discovered lands but was to finance himself all exploration.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and about 200 men, Léon set out from Puerto Rico in March 1513.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In April, they sighted land and named it *La Florida*—because it was Easter (Florida) season—believing it was an island, becoming credited as the first European to land in the continent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The arrival location has been disputed between St.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Augustine, Ponce de León Inlet and Melbourne Beach.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed south for further exploration and on 8 April encountered a current so strong that it pushed them backward: this was the first encounter with the Gulf Stream that would soon become the primary route for eastbound ships leaving the Spanish Indies bound for Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They explored down the coast reaching Biscayne Bay, Dry Tortugas and then sailing southwest in an attempt to circle Cuba to return, reaching Grand Bahama on July.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1517, Cuba's governor Diego Velázquez de Cuéllar commissioned a fleet under the command of Hernández de Córdoba to explore the Yucatán Peninsula.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They reached the coast where Mayans invited them to land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They were attacked at night and only a remnant of the crew returned.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Velázquez then commissioned another expedition led by his nephew Juan de Grijalva, who sailed south along the coast to Tabasco, part of the Aztec Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1518, Velázquez gave the mayor of the capital of Cuba, Hernán Cortés, the command of an expedition to secure the interior of Mexico but, due to an old gripe between them, revoked the charter.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In February 1519, Cortés went ahead anyway, in an act of open mutiny.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With about 11 ships, 500 men, 13 horses, and a small number of cannons he landed in Yucatán, in Mayan territory, claiming the land for the Spanish crown.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From Trinidad he proceeded to Tabasco and won a battle against the natives.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Among the vanquished was Marina (La Malinche), his future mistress, who knew both (Aztec) Nahuatl language and Maya, becoming a valuable interpreter and counsellor.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In July, his men took over Veracruz and he placed himself under direct orders of new king Charles I of Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] There Cortés asked for a meeting with Aztec emperor Moctezuma II, who repeatedly refused.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They headed to Tenochtitlan and on the way made alliances with several tribes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In October, accompanied by about 3,000 Tlaxcaltec they marched to Cholula, the second largest city in central Mexico.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Either to instill fear upon the Aztecs waiting for him or (as he later claimed) wishing to make an example when he feared native treachery, they massacred thousands of unarmed members of the nobility gathered at the central plaza and partially burned the city.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 8 November, Cortés and his large army were welcomed by Moctezuma II in Tenochtitlan, who hoped to learn about them to eventually defeat them.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Moctezuma gave lavish gifts, which led Cortés to plunder the city.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés claimed the Aztecs saw him as an emissary or incarnation of the god Quetzalcōātl, though this is contested by few historians.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon learning that his men had been attacked on the coast, Cortés took Moctezuma hostage in his palace, demanding tribute for King Charles.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Meanwhile, Velasquez sent another expedition, led by Pánfilo de Narváez, to oppose Cortès, arriving in Mexico in April 1520 with 1,100 men.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés left 200 men in Tenochtitlan and took the rest to confront Narvaez, whom he overcame, convincing his men to join him.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In Tenochtitlán, one of Cortés's lieutenants committed a massacre in the Great Temple, triggering local rebellion.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Cortés speedily returned, attempting the support of Moctezuma but the Aztec emperor was killed, possibly stoned by his subjects.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spaniards fled for Tlaxcala during the *Noche Triste*, where they managed a narrow escape while their back guard was massacred.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Much of the treasure looted was lost during this panicked escape.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After a battle in Otumba they reached Tlaxcala, having lost 870 men.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Having prevailed with the assistance of allies and reinforcements from Cuba, Cortés besieged Tenochtitlán and captured its ruler Cuauhtémoc in August 1521.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As the Aztec Empire ended, he claimed the city for Spain and renamed it Mexico City.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A first attempt to explore western South America was undertaken in 1522 by Pascual de Andagoya.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Native South Americans told him about a gold-rich territory on a river called Pirú.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Having reached San Juan River (Colombia), Andagoya fell ill and returned to Panama, where he spread the news about "Pirú" as the legendary El Dorado.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] These, along with the accounts of the success of Hernán Cortés, caught the attention of Pizarro.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Francisco Pizarro had accompanied Balboa in the crossing of the Isthmus of Panama.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, he formed a partnership with priest Hernando de Luque and soldier Diego de Almagro to explore the south, agreeing to divide the profits.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They dubbed the enterprise the "*Empresa del Levante*": Pizarro would command, Almagro would provide military and food supplies, and Luque would be in charge of finances and additional provisions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 13 September 1524, the first of three expeditions set out to conquer Peru with 80 men and 40 horses.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The venture failed, halting in Colombia due to bad weather, hunger, and conflicts with locals; Almagro lost an eye.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Their route was marked by *Puerto Deseado* (desired port), *Puerto del Hambre* (port of hunger), and *Puerto quemado* (burned port).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two years later, a second expedition began with reluctant permission from the Governor of Panama.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In August 1526, they departed with two ships, 160 men, and horses.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Upon reaching the San Juan River, Pizarro explored swampy coasts, while Almagro sought reinforcements.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's pilot, sailing south and crossing the equator, captured a raft from Tumbes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To his surprise, the raft carried coveted textiles, ceramics, gold, silver, and emeralds, becoming the expedition's main focus.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro later joined with reinforcements, and despite challenging conditions, they reached Atacames, where a sizable native population under Inca rule was observed, though they did not land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro, safe near the coast, sent Almagro and Luque for reinforcements with proof of the rumoured gold.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The new governor rejected a third expedition, ordering everyone back to Panama.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Almagro and Luque seized the chance to rejoin Pizarro.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] At *Isla de Gallo*, Pizarro drew a line, presenting the choice between Peru's riches and Panama's poverty.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Thirteen men, The Famous Thirteen, stayed and headed to *La Isla Gorgona*, staying seven months until provisions arrived.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They sailed south and by April 1528, reached northwestern Peru's Tumbes region, warmly received by the *Tumpis*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's men reported incredible riches, llama sightings, and the natives named them "Children of the Sun" for their fair complexion and brilliant armour.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They decided to return to Panama to prepare a final expedition, sailing south through named territories like Cabo Blanco, port of Payta, Sechura, Punta de Aguja, Santa Cruz, and Trujillo, reaching the ninth degree south.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the spring of 1528, Pizarro sailed for Spain, where he had an interview with king Charles I.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The king heard of his expeditions in lands rich in gold and silver and promised to support him.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The *Capitulación de Toledo* authorized Pizarro to proceed with the conquest of Peru.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro was then able to convince many friends and relatives to join: his brothers Hernándo Pizarro, Juan Pizarro, Gonzalo Pizarro, and also Francisco de Orellana, who would later explore the Amazon River, as well as his cousin Pedro Pizarro.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pizarro's third and final expedition left Panama for Peru on 27 December 1530.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With three ships and one hundred and eighty men, they landed near Ecuador and sailed to Tumbes, finding the place destroyed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They entered the interior and established the first Spanish settlement in Peru, San Miguel de Piura.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] One of the men returned with an Incan envoy and an invitation for a meeting.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Since the last meeting, the Inca had begun a civil war and Atahualpa had been resting in northern Peru following the defeat of his brother Huáscar.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After marching for two months, they approached Atahualpa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He refused the Spanish, saying he would be "no man's tributary".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] There were fewer than 200 Spanish to his 80,000 soldiers, but Pizarro attacked and won against the Incan army in the Battle of Cajamarca, taking Atahualpa captive at the so-called Ransom Room.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite fulfilling his promise of filling one room with gold and two with silver, he was convicted for killing his brother and plotting against Pizarro, and was executed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the Spanish had sealed the conquest of Peru, Jauja in fertile Mantaro Valley was established as Peru's provisional capital, but it was too far up in the mountains, and Pizarro founded the city of Lima on 18 January 1535, which Pizarro considered one of the most important acts in his life.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1543, three Portuguese traders accidentally became the first Westerners to reach and trade with Japan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] According to Fernão Mendes Pinto, who claimed to be in this journey, they arrived at Tanegashima, where the locals were impressed by firearms that would be immediately made by the Japanese on a large scale.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Spanish conquest of the Philippines was ordered by Philip II of Spain, and Andrés de Urdaneta was the designated commander.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta agreed to accompany the expedition but refused to command and Miguel López de Legazpi was appointed instead.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The expedition set sail in November 1564.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After spending some time on the islands, Legazpi sent Urdaneta back to find a better return route.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Urdaneta set sail from San Miguel on the island of Cebu on 1 June 1565, but was obliged to sail as far as 38 degrees North latitude to obtain favorable winds.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He reasoned that the trade winds of the Pacific might move in a gyre as the Atlantic winds did.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] If in the Atlantic, ships made the *Volta do mar* to pick up winds that would bring them back from Madeira, then, he reasoned, by sailing far to the north before heading east, he would pick up trade winds to bring him back to North America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His hunch paid off, and he hit the coast near Cape Mendocino, California, then followed the coast south.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The ship reached the port of Acapulco, on 8 October 1565, having traveled 12,000 miles (19,000 kilometres) in 130 days.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Fourteen of his crew died; only Urdaneta and Felipe de Salcedo, nephew of López de Legazpi, had strength enough to cast the anchors.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Thus, a cross-Pacific Spanish route was established, between Mexico and the Philippines.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] For a long time, these routes were used by the Manila galleons, thereby creating a trade link joining China, the Americas, and Europe via the combined trans-Pacific and trans-Atlantic routes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] European nations outside Iberia did not recognize the Treaty of Tordesillas between Portugal and Castile, nor did they recognize Pope Alexander VI's donation of the Spanish finds in the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England each had a long maritime tradition and had been engaging in privateering.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite Iberian protections, the new technologies and maps soon made their way north.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the marriage of Henry VIII of England and Catherine of Aragon failed to produce a male heir and Henry failed to obtain a papal dispensation to annul his marriage, he broke with the Roman Catholic Church and established himself as head of the Church of England.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This added religious conflict to political conflict.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] When much of The Netherlands became Protestant, it sought political and religious independence from Catholic Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1568, the Dutch rebelled against the rule of Philip II of Spain leading to the Eighty Years' War.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The war between England and Spain also broke out.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1580, Philip II became King of Portugal, as heir to its Crown.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Although he ruled Portugal and its empire as separate from the Spanish Empire, the union of the crowns produced a Catholic superpower, which England and the Netherlands challenged.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the eighty-year Dutch War of Independence, Philip's troops conquered the important trading cities of Bruges and Ghent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Antwerp, then the most important port in the world, fell in 1585.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Protestant population was given two years to settle affairs before leaving the city.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Those were mainly skilled craftsmen, rich merchants of the port cities and refugees that fled religious persecution, particularly Sephardic Jews from Portugal and Spain and, later, the Huguenots from France.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Pilgrim Fathers also spent time there before going to the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This mass immigration was an important driving force: a small port in 1585, Amsterdam quickly transformed into one of the most important commercial centres in the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the failure of the Spanish Armada in 1588, there was a huge expansion of maritime trade even though the defeat of the English Armada would confirm the naval supremacy of the Spanish navy over the emergent competitors.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch maritime power rose quickly as Dutch sailors, skilled in navigation and mapmaking, engaged with Portuguese voyages.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1592, Cornelis de Houtman gathered information on the Spice Islands in Lisbon.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The same year, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten published a detailed travel report in Amsterdam, providing navigation instructions for reaching the East Indies and Japan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Following this, Houtman led the Dutch's first exploratory voyage, discovering a new route from Madagascar to the Sunda Strait and securing a treaty with the Banten Sultan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Dutch also demonstrated their maritime strength by seizing Malacca from Portugal in 1641, following a series of battles that began in 1602.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch and British interest, fed on new information, led to a movement of commercial expansion, and the foundation of English (1600) and Dutch (1602) chartered companies.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch, French, and English sent ships which flouted the Portuguese monopoly, concentrated mostly on the coastal areas, which proved unable to defend against such a vast and dispersed venture.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The 1497 English expedition authorized by Henry VII of England was led by Italian Venetian John Cabot (Giovanni Caboto); it was the first of a series of French and English missions exploring North America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Mariners from the Italian peninsula played an important role in early explorations, most especially Genoese mariner Christopher Columbus.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With its major conquests of central Mexico and Peru and discoveries of silver, Spain put limited efforts into exploring the northern part of the Americas; its resources were concentrated in Central and South America where more wealth had been found.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] These other European expeditions were initially motivated by the same idea as Columbus, namely a westerly shortcut to the Asian mainland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After the existence of "another ocean" (the Pacific) was confirmed by Balboa in 1513, there still remained the motivation of potentially finding an oceanic Northwest Passage for Asian trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This was not discovered until the early twentieth century, but other possibilities were found, although nothing on the scale of the spectacular ones of the Spanish.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the early 17th century colonists from a number of Northern European states began to settle on the east coast of North America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1524, Italian Giovanni da Verrazzano sailed under the authority of Francis I of France, who was motivated by indignation over the division of the world between Portuguese and Spanish.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Verrazzano explored the Atlantic Coast of North America, from South Carolina to Newfoundland, and was the first recorded European to visit what would later become the Virginia Colony and the United States.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In the same year Estêvão Gomes, a Portuguese cartographer who had sailed in Ferdinand Magellan's fleet, explored Nova Scotia, sailing South through Maine, where he entered what is now New York Harbor, the Hudson River and eventually reached Florida in August 1525.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] As a result of his expedition, the 1529 Diogo Ribeiro world map outlines the East coast of North America almost perfectly.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Europeans explored the Pacific Coast beginning in the mid-16th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Spaniard Francisco de Ulloa explored the Pacific coast of present-day Mexico including the Gulf of California, proving that Baja California was a peninsula.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Despite his report based on first-hand information, the myth persisted in Europe that California was an island.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His account provided the first recorded use of the name "California".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] João Rodrigues Cabrilho, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, was the first European to set foot in California, landing on 28 September 1542, on the shores of San Diego Bay and claiming California for Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He also landed on San Miguel, one of the Channel Islands, and continued as far north as Point Reyes on the mainland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After his death, the crew continued exploring as far north as Oregon.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The English privateer Francis Drake sailed along the coast in 1579 north of Cabrillo's landing site while circumnavigating the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake had a long and largely successful career attacking Spanish settlements in the Caribbean islands and the mainland so for the English, he was a great hero and fervent Protestant, but for the Spanish, he was "a frightening monster".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake played a major role in the defeat of the Spanish Armada in 1588 but led an armada himself to the Spanish Caribbean that was unsuccessful in dislodging the Spanish.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1579, the ship briefly made first landfall at South Cove, Cape Arago, just south of Coos Bay, Oregon, and then sailed south while searching for a suitable harbor to repair his damaged ship.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 17 June, Drake and his crew found a protected cove when they landed on the Pacific coast of what is now Northern California near Point Reyes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] While ashore, he claimed the area for Queen Elizabeth I of England as Nova Albion or New Albion.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] To document and assert his claim, Drake posted an engraved plate of brass to claim sovereignty for Queen Elizabeth and her successors on the throne.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake's landfalls on the west coast of North America are one small part of his 1577–1580 circumnavigation of the globe, the first captain of his own ship to do so.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Drake died in 1596 off the coast of Panama, following injuries from a raid.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He explored the Hudson River and laid the foundation for Dutch colonization of the region.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Hudson's final expedition ranged farther north in search of the Northwest Passage, leading to his discovery of the Hudson Strait and Hudson Bay.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After wintering in James Bay, Hudson tried to press on with his voyage in the spring of 1611, but his crew mutinied and they cast him adrift.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] France, the Netherlands, and England sought a sea route to Asia after finding none through Africa or South America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] With no route through the Americas, they focused on northern passages, driving European exploration of the Arctic coasts.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The idea of a link between the Atlantic and Pacific was first proposed by Russian diplomat Gerasimov in 1525, though Russian Pomors had explored parts of the route as early as the 11th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1553, English explorer Hugh Willoughby with chief pilot Richard Chancellor were sent out with three vessels in search of a passage by London's Company of Merchant Adventurers to New Lands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] During the voyage across the Barents Sea, Willoughby thought he saw islands to the north, and islands called Willoughby's Land were shown on maps published by Plancius and Mercator into the 1640s.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The vessels were separated by "terrible whirlwinds" in the Norwegian Sea and Willoughby sailed into a bay near the present border between Finland and Russia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] His ships with the frozen crews, including Captain Willoughby and his journal, were found by Russian fishermen a year later.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Richard Chancellor was able to drop anchor in the White Sea and make his way overland to Moscow and Ivan the Terrible's court, opening trade with Russia and the Company of Merchant Adventurers became the Muscovy Company.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In June 1576, English mariner Martin Frobisher led an expedition consisting of three ships and 35 men to search for a north-west passage around North America.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The voyage was supported by the Muscovy Company, the same merchants that hired Hugh Willoughby to find a northeast passage above Russia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Violent storms sank one ship and forced another to turn back but Frobisher and the remaining ship reached the coast of Labrador in July.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] A few days later they came upon the mouth of what is now Frobisher Bay.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher believed it to be the entrance to a north-west passage and named it Frobisher's Strait and claimed Baffin Island for Queen Elizabeth.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] After some preliminary exploration, Frobisher returned to England.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He commanded two subsequent voyages in 1577 and 1578 but failed to find the hoped-for passage.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Frobisher brought to England his ships laden with ore, but it was found to be worthless and damaged his reputation as an explorer.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He remains an important early historical figure in Canada.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 5 June 1594, Dutch cartographer Willem Barentsz departed from Texel in a fleet of three ships to enter the Kara Sea, with the hopes of finding the Northeast Passage above Siberia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] At Williams Island the crew encountered a polar bear for the first time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They managed to bring it on board, but the bear rampaged and was killed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached the west coast of Novaya Zemlya and followed it northward, before being forced to turn back in the face of large icebergs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The following year, Prince Maurice of Orange named him chief pilot of a new expedition of six ships, loaded with merchant wares that the Dutch hoped to trade with China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The party came across Samoyed "wild men" but eventually turned back upon discovering the Kara Sea frozen.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1596, the States-General offered a high reward for anybody who *successfully* navigated the Northeast Passage.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The Town Council of Amsterdam purchased and outfitted two small ships, captained by Jan Rijp and Jacob van Heemskerck, to search for the elusive channel, under the command of Barents.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They set off in May, and in June discovered Bear Island and Spitsbergen, sighting its northwest coast.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They saw a large bay, later called Raudfjorden and entered Magdalenefjorden, which they named *Tusk Bay*, sailing into the northern entrance of Forlandsundet, which they called *Keerwyck*, but were forced to turn back because of a shoal.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 28 June they rounded the northern point of Prins Karls Forland, which they named *Vogelhoek*, on account of a large number of birds, and sailed south, passing Isfjorden and Bellsund, which were labelled on Barentsz's chart as *Grooten Inwyck* and *Inwyck*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The ships once again reached Bear Island on 1 July, which led to a disagreement.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] They parted ways, with Barentsz continuing northeast, while Rijp headed north.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz reached Novaya Zemlya and, to avoid becoming entrapped in ice, headed for the Kara Strait but became stuck within the icebergs and floes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Stranded, the 16-man crew was forced to spend the winter on the ice.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] The crew used lumber from their ship to build a lodge they called *Het Behouden Huys* (The Kept House).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dealing with extreme cold, they used merchant fabrics to make additional blankets and clothing and caught Arctic foxes in primitive traps, as well as polar bears.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] When June arrived, and the ice had still not loosened its grip on the ship, scurvy-ridden survivors took two small boats out into the sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Barentsz died at sea on 20 June 1597, while studying charts.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] It took seven more weeks for the boats to reach Kola where they were rescued by a Russian merchant vessel.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Only 12 crewmen remained, reaching Amsterdam in November.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Two of Barentsz' crewmembers later published their journals, Jan Huyghen van Linschoten, who had accompanied him on the first two voyages, and Gerrit de Veer who had acted as the ship's carpenter on the last.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Juan Fernández, sailing from Chile in 1576, claimed he had discovered the Southern Continent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Luís Vaz de Torres, a Galician navigator working for the Spanish Crown, proved the existence of a passage south of New Guinea, now known as Torres Strait.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Pedro Fernandes de Queirós, a Portuguese navigator sailing for the Spanish Crown, saw a large island south of New Guinea in 1606, which he named *Austrialia del Espiritu Santo* (transl.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Southern-Austrian Land of the Holy Spirit).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He represented this to the King of Spain as the *Terra Australis incognita*, but it was present-day Vanuatu rather than Australia or Antarctica.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Dutch navigator and colonial governor, Willem Janszoon sailed from the Netherlands for the East Indies for the third time on 18 December 1603, as captain of *Duyfken* (or *Duijfken*, meaning 'Little Dove'), one of twelve ships of the great fleet of Steven van der Hagen.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Once in the Indies, Janszoon was sent to search for other outlets of trade, particularly in "the great land of Nova Guinea and other East and Southlands".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 18 November 1605, *Duyfken* sailed from Banten to the coast of western New Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon then crossed the eastern end of the Arafura Sea, without becoming aware of the Torres Strait, into the Gulf of Carpentaria.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] On 26 February 1606, he made landfall at the Pennefather River on the western shore of Cape York in Queensland, near the modern town of Weipa.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] This is the first recorded European landfall on the Australian continent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Janszoon proceeded to chart some 320 kilometres (199 mi) of the coastline, which he thought was a southerly extension of New Guinea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] In 1615, Jacob Le Maire and Willem Schouten's rounding of Cape Horn proved that Tierra del Fuego was a relatively small island.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] From 1642 to 1644, Abel Tasman, also a Dutch explorer and merchant in the service of the VOC, circumnavigated New Holland proving that Australia was not part of the mythical southern continent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] He was the first known European expedition to reach the islands of Van Diemen's Land (now Tasmania) and New Zealand and to sight the Fiji islands, which he did in 1643.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p02] Tasman, his navigator Visscher, and his merchant Gilsemans also mapped substantial portions of Australia, New Zealand, and the Pacific islands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the mid-16th century, the Tsardom of Russia conquered the Tatar khanates of Kazan and Astrakhan, thus annexing the entire Volga region and opening the way to the Ural Mountains.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The colonization of the new easternmost lands of Russia and further onslaught eastward was led by the rich merchants Stroganovs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivan the Terrible granted vast estates near the Urals as well as tax privileges to Anikey Stroganov, who organized large-scale migration to these lands.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Stroganovs developed farming, hunting, saltworks, fishing, and ore mining on the Urals and established trade with Siberian tribes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Around 1577, Semyon Stroganov and other sons of Anikey Stroganov hired a Cossack leader called Yermak to protect their lands from the attacks of Khan Kuchum.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1580, Stroganovs and Yermak came up with the idea of a military expedition to Siberia, to fight Kuchum in his own land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1581, Yermak began his voyage into the depths of Siberia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After a few victories over the Khan's army, Yermak's people defeated the main forces of Kuchum on Irtysh River in the three-day Battle of Chuvash Cape in 1582.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The remains of the Khan's army retreated to the steppes, and thus Yermak captured the Khanate of Sibir, including its capital Qashliq near modern Tobolsk.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kuchum still was strong and suddenly attacked Yermak in 1585 in the dead of night, killing most of his people.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Yermak was wounded and tried to swim across the Wagay River (Irtysh's tributary), but drowned under the weight of his own chain mail.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks had to withdraw from Siberia completely, but thanks to Yermak's having explored all the main river routes in West Siberia, Russians successfully reclaimed all his conquests just several years later.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the early 17th century, the eastward movement of Russians was slowed by the internal problems in the country during the Time of Troubles.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Very soon, exploration and colonization of the huge territories of Siberia resumed, led mostly by Cossacks hunting for valuable furs and ivory.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] While Cossacks came from the Southern Urals, another wave of Russians came by the Arctic Ocean.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] These were Pomors from the Russian North, who already had been making fur trade with Mangazeya in the north of Western Siberia for quite a long time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1607, the settlement of Turukhansk was founded on the northern Yenisey River, near the mouth of Lower Tunguska.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1619, Yeniseysk ostrog was founded on the mid-Yenisey at the mouth of the Upper Tunguska.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1620 and 1624, a group of fur hunters led by Demid Pyanda left Turukhansk and explored some 1,430 miles (2,300 kilometres) of the Lower Tunguska, wintering in the proximity of the Vilyuy and Lena Rivers.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] According to later legendary accounts (folktales collected a century after the fact), Pyanda discovered the Lena.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He allegedly explored some 1,500 miles (2,400 kilometres) of its length, reaching as far as central Yakutia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He returned up the Lena until it became too rocky and shallow, and portaged to the Angara River.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In this way, Pyanda may have become the first Russian to meet Yakuts and Buryats.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He built new boats and explored some 870 miles (1,400 kilometres) of the Angara, finally reaching Yeniseysk and discovering that the Angara (a Buryat name) and Upper Tunguska (Verkhnyaya Tunguska, as initially known by Russians) are one and the same river.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1627, Pyotr Beketov was appointed Yenisei voevoda in Siberia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He successfully carried out the voyage to collect taxes from the Zabaykalye Buryats, becoming the first Russian to step in Buryatia.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He founded the first Russian settlement there, Rybinsky ostrog.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Beketov was sent to the Lena River in 1631, where in 1632 he founded Yakutsk and sent his Cossacks to explore the Aldan River and farther down the Lena, to found new fortresses, and to collect taxes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Yakutsk soon turned into a major starting point for further Russian expeditions eastward, southward and northward.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Maksim Perfilyev, who earlier had been one of the founders of Yeniseysk, founded Bratsk ostrog on the Angara in 1631.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1638, Perfilyev became the first Russian to step into Transbaikalia, travelling there from Yakutsk.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Kurbat Ivanov led a group of Cossacks from Yakutsk to the south of the Baikal Mountains and discovered Lake Baikal, visiting its Olkhon Island.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ivanov later made the first chart and description of Baikal.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1639, a group of explorers led by Ivan Moskvitin became the first Russians to reach the Pacific Ocean and to discover the Sea of Okhotsk, having built a winter camp on its shore at the Ulya River mouth.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Cossacks learned from the locals about the large Amur River far to the south.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1640, they apparently sailed south, and explored the south-eastern shores of the Okhotsk Sea, perhaps reaching the mouth of the Amur River and possibly discovering the Shantar Islands on their way back.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Based on Moskvitin's account, Kurbat Ivanov drew the first Russian map of the Far East in 1642.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1643, Vassili Poyarkov crossed the Stanovoy Range and reached the upper Zeya River in the country of the Daurs, who were paying tribute to the Manchus.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After wintering, in 1644, Poyarkov pushed down the Zeya and became the first Russian to reach the Amur River.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He sailed down the Amur and finally discovered the mouth of that great river from land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Since his Cossacks provoked the enmity of the locals behind, Poyarkov chose a different way back.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They built boats and in 1645, sailed along the Sea of Okhotsk coast to the Ulya River and spent the next winter in the huts that had been built by Ivan Moskvitin six years earlier.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1644, Mikhail Stadukhin discovered the Kolyma River and founded Srednekolymsk.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A merchant named Fedot Alekseyevich Popov organized a further expedition eastward, and Semyon Dezhnyov became a captain of one of the kochi.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1648, they sailed from Srednekolymsk down to the Arctic and after some time they rounded Cape Dezhnyov, thus becoming the first explorers to pass through the Bering Strait and discover Chukotka and the Bering Sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] All their Kochi and most of their men (including Popov himself) were lost in storms and clashes with the natives.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A small group led by Dezhnyov reached the mouth of the Anadyr River and sailed up it in 1649, having built new boats from the wreckage.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They founded Anadyrsk and were stranded there until Stadukhin found them, coming from Kolyma by land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, Stadukhin set off south in 1651 and discovered Penzhin Bay on the northern coast of the Okhotsk Sea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He also may have explored the western shores of Kamchatka.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1649 to 1650, Yerofey Khabarov became the second Russian to explore the Amur River.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Through the Olyokma, Tungir, and Shilka Rivers he reached Amur (Dauriya), returned to Yakutsk and then back to Amur with a larger force in 1650–1653.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This time he was met with armed resistance.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He built winter quarters at Albazin, then sailed down Amur and found Achansk, which preceded the present-day Khabarovsk, defeating or evading large armies of Daurs, Manchus, Chinese, and Koreans on his way.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] He charted the Amur in his *Draft of the Amur river*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Subsequently, the Russians held on to the Amur region until 1689, when by the Treaty of Nerchinsk this land was assigned to the Qing Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It was returned by the Treaty of Aigun in 1858.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1659 to 1665, Kurbat Ivanov was the next head of Anadyrsky ostrog after Semyon Dezhnev.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1660, he sailed from Anadyr Bay to Cape Dezhnyov.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By the mid-17th century, the Russians established the borders of their country close to modern ones, and explored almost the whole of Siberia, except the eastern Kamchatka and some regions north of the Arctic Circle.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The conquest of Kamchatka later would be achieved in the early 1700s by Vladimir Atlasov, while the discovery of the Arctic coastline and Alaska would be completed by the Great Northern Expedition in 1733–1743.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] European overseas expansion led to contact between the Old and New Worlds producing the Columbian exchange.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It started the global silver trade between the Americas, Europe, and China, and led to direct European involvement in the Chinese porcelain trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] It involved the transfer of goods unique from one hemisphere to another.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From the Old World, Europeans brought cattle, horses, and sheep to the New World, and from the New World Europeans received tobacco, potatoes, tomatoes, and maize.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Other items and commodities becoming important in global trade were the tobacco, sugarcane, and cotton crops of the Americas, along with the gold and silver brought from the American continent not only to Europe, but elsewhere in the Old World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The formation of new transoceanic links and expansion of European influence led to the Age of Imperialism, which began during the Age of Discovery, during which colonial powers from Europe colonized most territory on the planet.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Combined with the introduction of infectious diseases from Europe, these events led to a drastic decrease of the American Indian population.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] American Indian accounts of European colonization were summarized by scholar Peter Mancall: "The arrival of Europeans brought death, displacement, sorrow, and despair to Native Americans".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In some areas, like North America, Central America, Australia, New Zealand, and Argentina, indigenous peoples were poorly treated, driven off their lands, and reduced to dependent minorities in the territory.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Similarly, in East and West Africa, local states supplied the appetite of European slave traders, changing the complexion of coastal African states and fundamentally altering the nature of slavery in Africa, causing impacts on societies and economies deep inland.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In North America, there were many conflicts between European colonists and American Indians.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Maize and manioc were introduced into Africa in the 16th century by the Portuguese.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] They are now important staple foods, replacing native African crops.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Crosby speculated that increased production of maize, manioc, and other New World crops led to heavier concentrations of population in the areas from which slavers captured their victims.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the global silver trade, China was stimulated by trade with the Portuguese, Spaniards, and Dutch.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although global, much of that silver ended up with the Chinese, and China dominated silver imports.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Between 1600 and 1800, China received 100 tons of silver on average per year.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] A large populace near the Lower Yangtze averaged hundreds of taels of silver per household in the late 16th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] More than 150,000 tons of silver were shipped from Potosí by the end of the 18th century.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From 1500 to 1800, Mexico and Peru produced about 80% of the world's silver, with more than 30% of it eventually ending up in China (largely because European merchants used it to purchase exotic Chinese commodities).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the late 16th and early 17th century, Japan was exporting heavily into China and foreign trade at large.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Trade with European powers and the Japanese brought in significant amounts of silver, which then replaced copper and paper banknotes as the common medium of exchange in China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] During the last decades of the Ming dynasty, the flow of silver into China was greatly diminished, thereby undermining state revenues and the entire Ming economy.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This damage to the economy was compounded by the effects on agriculture of the incipient Little Ice Age, natural calamities, crop failure, and sudden epidemics.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The ensuing breakdown of authority and people's livelihoods allowed rebel leaders such as Li Zicheng to challenge Ming authority.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] New crops that had come to Asia from the Americas, via the Spanish colonizers in the 16th century, contributed to Asia's population growth.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although the bulk of imports to China were silver, the Chinese also purchased New World crops from the Spanish Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] This included sweet potatoes, maize, and peanuts, foods that could be cultivated in lands where traditional Chinese staple crops—wheat, millet, and rice—could not grow, hence facilitating a rise in the population of China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the Song dynasty (960–1279), rice had become the major staple crop of the poor; after sweet potatoes were introduced to China around 1560, it gradually became the traditional food of the lower classes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The arrival of the Portuguese to Japan in 1543 initiated the Nanban trade period, with the Japanese adopting technologies and cultural practices, like the arquebus, European-style cuirasses, European ships, Christianity, decorative art, and language.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] After the Chinese had banned direct trade by Chinese merchants with Japan, the Portuguese filled this commercial vacuum as intermediaries.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Portuguese bought Chinese silk and sold it to the Japanese in return for Japanese-mined silver; since silver was more highly valued in China, the Portuguese could then use Japanese silver to buy even larger stocks of Chinese silk.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1573, after the Spaniards established a trading base in Manila, the Portuguese intermediary trade was trumped by the prime source of incoming silver to China from the Spanish Americas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Although China acted as the cog running the wheel of global trade during the 16th to 18th centuries, Japan's huge contribution of silver exports to China was critical to the world economy and China's liquidity and success with the commodity.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] As a wider variety of global luxury commodities entered the European markets by sea, previous European markets for luxury goods stagnated.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Atlantic trade largely supplanted pre-existing Italian and German trading powers which had relied on their Baltic, Russian, and Islamic trade links.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The new commodities also caused social change, as sugar, spices, silks, and chinawares entered the luxury markets of Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The European economic centre shifted from the Mediterranean to Western Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The city of Antwerp, part of the Duchy of Brabant, became "the centre of the *entire* international economy", and the richest city in Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Centred in Antwerp first and then Amsterdam, the Dutch Golden Age was tightly linked to the Age of Discovery.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] By 1549, the Portuguese empire sent annual trade missions to Shangchuan Island in China.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In 1557, they managed to convince the Ming court to agree on a legal port treaty that would establish Macau as an official Portuguese trade colony.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] From China, the major exports were silk and porcelain, adapted to meet European tastes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The Chinese export porcelains were held in such great esteem in Europe that, in English, *china* became a commonly used synonym for *porcelain*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak porcelain was among the first Chinese ware to arrive in Europe in significant quantities; only the richest could afford these early imports.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Soon the Dutch East India Company established trade with the East, having imported 6 million porcelain items from China to Europe between 1602 and 1682.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Kraak, mainly the blue and white porcelain, was imitated all over the world by potters in Arita, Japan and Persia—where Dutch merchants turned when the fall of the Ming dynasty rendered Chinese originals unavailable—and ultimately in delftware.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Dutch and later English delftware inspired by Chinese designs persisted from about 1630 to the mid-18th century alongside European patterns.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Antonio de Morga (1559–1636), a Spanish official in Manila, listed an extensive inventory of goods that were traded by Ming China at the turn of the 16th to 17th century, noting there were "rarities which, did I refer to them all, I would never finish, nor have sufficient paper for it".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Ebrey writes of the considerable size of commercial transactions: In one case a galleon to the Spanish territories in the New World carried over 50,000 pairs of silk stockings.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In return China imported mostly silver from Peruvian and Mexican mines, transported via Manila.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Chinese merchants were active in these trading ventures, and many emigrated to such places as the Philippines and Borneo to take advantage of the new commercial opportunities.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in gold and silver experienced by Spain coincided with a major inflationary cycle within Spain and Europe, known as the price revolution.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Spain had amassed large quantities of gold and silver from the New World.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] In the 1540s, large scale extraction of silver from Mexico began.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] During the 16th century, Spain held the equivalent of US$1.5 trillion (1990 terms) in gold and silver from New Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Being the most powerful European monarch at a time full of war and religious conflicts, the Habsburg rulers spent their wealth in wars and arts across Europe.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The spent silver, spread throughout a cash-starved Europe, caused widespread inflation.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The inflation was worsened by a growing population with a static production level, low salaries and a rising cost of living, which damaged local industry.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Increasingly, Spain became dependent on the revenues flowing in from the mercantile empire, leading to Spain's first bankruptcy in 1557 due to rising military costs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Philip II of Spain defaulted on debt payments in 1557, 1560, 1575, and 1596.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] The increase in prices as a result of currency circulation fuelled the growth of the commercial middle class in Europe, the *bourgeoisie*, which came to influence the politics and culture of many countries.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] One effect of the inflation, particularly in Great Britain, was that tenant farmers who held long-term leases from lords saw real decreases in rent.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-discovery-p03] Some lords opted to sell their leased land, giving rise to small, landowning farmers.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Despite using the same game engine and code similar to its predecessor's, development of *The Age of Kings* took a year longer than expected, forcing Ensemble Studios to release *Age of Empires: The Rise of Rome* in 1998 instead.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The design team focused on resolving significant issues in *Age of Empires*, but noted on release that some problems remained.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Reception of *Age of Empires II* was highly positive.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The significant number of new features was praised, as were the gameplay improvements.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] 3 months after its release, two million copies of *Age of Empires II* had been shipped, and it topped sales charts in seven countries.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game won multiple awards and is today considered a classic of its type, having had a significant impact on future games in its genre.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The original *Age of Empires II* and its 2000 expansion pack, *The Conquerors*, were later released as *The Gold Edition*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *Age of Empires II* is often considered one of the greatest games ever made.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] An updated high-definition graphics version of the game, *Age of Empires II: HD Edition*, was released in 2013.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The *HD Edition* includes the original game and the expansion *The Conquerors*, as well as new campaigns, civilizations, and updated graphics for high-resolution displays.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] A remaster, *Age of Empires II: Definitive Edition*, was released in November 2019.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Civilian units, called "villagers", are used to gather resources; they are either male or female—sex does not affect their abilities.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Resources can be used to train units, construct buildings, and research technologies, among other things; for example, players can research better armour for infantry units.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game features four types of resources: food, wood, gold, and stone.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Food is obtained by hunting animals, gathering berries, harvesting livestock, farming, and fishing, both from shore and from boats.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Wood is gathered by chopping down trees.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Gold is obtained from either gold mines, trade, or collecting relics in a monastery.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Villagers require checkpoints, typically depository buildings (town center, mining camp, mill, and lumber yard), in order to store gathered resources.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Each civilization can purchase upgrades that increase the rate of gathering these resources.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Players can also construct a marketplace for trade, where they can trade wood, stone, and food for gold, and use gold to buy other resources.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Market prices fluctuate with every transaction.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Furthermore, markets and docks can also generate gold by using trading carts or cogs, which are sent to visit foreign markets and ports; once they return to the player's market/dock, gold is added to the stockpile.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The amount of gold a trade unit earns on each trip is based on the distance it needed to travel to a foreign market; more gold is earned on longer trips.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It is possible to trade with enemies' markets or docks, but the player's trading units may be attacked or destroyed by enemy units in the process.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Players do not need to keep trading manually, because once they select the port or market the trading units continue to trade automatically and indefinitely.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] There are 5 campaigns in *The Age of Kings*, containing historically based scenarios such as Genghis Khan's invasion of Eurasia, Barbarossa's Crusade, and Saladin's defence of the Holy Land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] In the Joan of Arc and William Wallace campaigns, the player can control a unit based on its namesake; in others, players take orders from guiding spirits representative of the army's commander.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Additional game modes are available to the player in *The Age of Kings*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] One mode, random map, generates a map from one of several randomly chosen map-generating scripts, with players starting in the Dark Age with a Town Center, three villagers (or more depending on the civilization), and a scout unit.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game can be won through military conquest, by constructing a special building known as a Wonder and keeping it standing for a certain amount of time, or by obtaining control of all relics on the map for a set amount of time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Deathmatch mode allows players to begin with large amounts of resources, creating a focus on military dominance, while in the regicide mode each player is given a king unit, winning by killing all of the other monarchs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Every player has an ultimate limit to the number of units they can create—a population limit—but cannot immediately use this entire potential population.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The population capacity, which can be capped at anywhere between 25 and 200 in intervals of 25, is based on the number of houses, Castles, or Town Centers—the main building in a player's town—which have been built.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Each civilization in *The Age of Kings* has one or two special units that are exclusive to that civilization.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] These civilization-specific units are generally more powerful, but still follow the basic rock-paper-scissors model.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The monk is a special kind of military unit that has the ability to convert enemy units to the player's civilization, and to heal allied units.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Monks are also used to collect relics, which accumulate gold once held in the player's monastery—the more relics are captured, the faster the gold is accumulated.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Collecting all relics on the map is one method by which a player can win a random map game, depending on the victory condition.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Once a player has all the relics in their monasteries, a timer is shown to all players.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The player holding all of the relics wins if they maintain control of the relics for the length of the timer.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The civilizations have varying strengths and weaknesses with regards to economics, technology, and combat, and each has access to one or more different, very powerful "Unique Units".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Additionally, each civilization provides an individual team bonus in team games.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] To add variety, each civilization has a set of sound bites in its native language that are uttered by units when selected or instructed to perform a task.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Buildings in *The Age of Kings* are split into economic and military categories.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Buildings can research technologies and upgrades that increase economic, military, or unit-based efficiency, as well as provide resources for the player.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The most important economic building is the Town Center, where villagers are created, all types of resources can be stored, some technologies are researched, and the player can advance to the next Age.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The Town Center can fire arrows at enemy units if villagers or archers are garrisoned inside while enemy units are within range.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Other economic buildings include storage buildings for resources, farms, docks (the dock may also produce several military ships), and houses to support a higher population.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Military buildings include unit-producing buildings such as barracks, archery ranges, stables, and castles, as well as defensive buildings such as walls and towers.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Military buildings can conduct research to improve the abilities of military units, increasing their strength, defensive capabilities, or other capabilities.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Castles are a key offensive and defensive building as they can build trebuchets, train the civilization's "unique unit/s", and fire a hail of arrows at enemy units within range, with garrisoned units firing extra arrows.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Castles can only be built after a player has reached the Castle Age, although in some game options, players begin with an already-built castle as early as the Dark Age.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] After advancing to the Imperial Age, players can also construct a Wonder, an expensive non-military building.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] On many gameplay modes building a Wonder triggers a victory countdown; unless it is destroyed within a certain timeframe, the player who built it wins.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Every civilization's Wonder is in the shape of a real-world landmark unique to that historical culture.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Prior to the completion of *Age of Empires*, Ensemble Studios had signed a contract with Microsoft for a sequel.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The design team chose to set *The Age of Kings* in the Middle Ages as a logical progression from the ancient era setting of *Age of Empires*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The design team was conscious of attempting to capture the broad appeal of the first game without making the game's design too similar.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Nonetheless, they attempted to appeal to the vast demographic who played *Age of Empires*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *The Age of Kings*'s design team intended to complete the game within a year by using code from the original and reusing the Genie game engine.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Several months into the process they found they would not be able to complete a game of the quality they sought in that time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Ensemble Studios informed Microsoft they would need another year and instead created *Age of Empires: The Rise of Rome*, an easily developed expansion pack of *Age of Empires*, as a compromise which could be released for Christmas 1998.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] To help meet the next year's deadline, additional programmers, artists, and designers were employed.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] To overcome another significant objection to the original game—its path-finding—the team completely redesigned the game engine's movement system.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game took two years to complete with 50 full-time employees on a budget of less than $10 million.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The original *Age of Empires* was criticized for its artificial intelligence (AI), which did not "cheat" by attributing itself extra resources or using other techniques the human player could not, making it easier to defeat than in many other real-time strategy games.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] For *The Age of Kings*, Ensemble Studios attempted to develop a more powerful AI system that still did not compromise by cheating.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Industry veteran Mario Grimani led Ensemble Studios in the creation of the new system.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *The Age of Kings* saw the introduction of a triggers system for its scenario editor.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The triggers allow messages to be displayed, or actions to take place, based on pre-set criteria or "events".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The scenario editor was also improved by the new AI system.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The AI and trigger systems interacted regularly in the single-player campaigns.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The team was less successful in resolving other issues; programmer Matt Pritchard complained following the release of *Age of Empires* that there was still no process by which patches could be issued.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Extensive cheating in multiplayer games of *Age of Empires* came as a result of several bugs in the game, which resulted in Microsoft promising Ensemble Studios there would be a patch process for *The Age of Kings*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Upon release, there were several bugs that needed immediate attention, but the patch process was not yet ready.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The first patch was released 11 months later.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Pritchard also described problems with Microsoft's DirectPlay API following the release of *The Age of Kings*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] He explained, "One of its biggest problems is documentation and testing of the lesser-used portions of the API...
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Ensemble Studios developed a new terrain system for *The Age of Kings*, with 3D presentation capabilities that were vastly superior to those of *Age of Empires*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Pritchard noted an improvement in the team's artistic abilities following their work on the past two games, and he is noted as saying that "*AoK* became a showcase for their improved talent".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] However, he complained about the lack of an art asset management tool, while other departments gained new tools and automated procedures to assist in design and play testing.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The soundtrack for *The Age of Kings* was directed by Stephen Rippy, who has since taken that role for all games in the *Age of Empires* series.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Music for the game was split into two categories.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] For "in-game" music, Rippy's team took musical elements from a variety of cultures and combined them to create a mixed sound.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] "Pre-game" music was designed to be unique to the civilization in question.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Campaigns based on historical figures would include "a theme that will at least be rooted in [the character's] culture".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] A demo of *The Age of Kings* was released on October 16, 1999.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It featured the learning campaign, a sample of a random map game, and the ability to play via the MSN Gaming Zone.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Much to Ensemble Studios' disappointment, numerous incomplete versions of the game were leaked.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] These were picked up by warez sites, and sold illegally throughout the Pacific Rim; warez versions of the game were even sold outside Microsoft's offices in South Korea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] In January 2000, three months after its release, Microsoft had shipped two million copies of *The Age of Kings*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game topped sales charts in the United States, Japan, the United Kingdom, Germany, France, Australia, and South Korea.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It spent the next two and a half years on top 20 sales lists.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *The Age of Kings* was the top-selling game in October 1999, and the fourth highest-selling game in 1999.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game's sales in the United States alone totaled 469,376 by the end of 1999, which drew revenues of $20.2 million, the second-highest domestic gross that year behind *SimCity 3000*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Domestic sales rose another 442,318 units ($19.56 million) from January through October 2000, according to PC Data.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It finished the year as the seventh-largest computer game hit in the United States, with 595,016 in sales and $26.2 million in revenue.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *Age of Empires II*'s domestic success continued in 2001: with sales of 478,557 units ($19.4 million), it claimed tenth place for the year.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] In the German market, *Age of Empires II* debuted in first place on Media Control's sales charts during October 1999, and by March 2000 had spent 17 weeks in the rankings.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It received the Verband der Unterhaltungssoftware Deutschland's (VUD) "Platinum" award within one month of release, indicating sales of 200,000 units across Germany, Switzerland, and Austria.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] By the end of February 2000, it had reached "Double-Platinum" status (400,000 sales) and become the German market's "most successful PC game of the past 12 months", according to the VUD.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game later received a "Platinum" sales award from the Entertainment and Leisure Software Publishers Association (ELSPA) for at least 300,000 copies sold in the United Kingdom.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Between the 2019 re-release and global lockdowns due to the COVID-19 pandemic in 2020, the game has seen a resurgence in popularity.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] According to *Eurogamer*'s Geoff Richards, "the list of new features and improvements over the original game is over a page long".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *GamePro*'s review similarly focused on "new additions to the genre itself" which it argued made *The Age of Kings* outstanding.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] These included the idle unit button and town bell.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *GameSpy*'s Carlos Salgado was appreciative of other features; he praised the ability to create individual profiles for different players and to customize hotkeys.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] House also praised the gameplay interface, which he said "couldn't be simpler", as well as the advanced unit grouping and path-finding systems.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Nash Werner of *GamePro* said that the battlefield formation tools were wonderful, and complained only that they could not be assigned to naval units.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *Computer and Video Games* generally agreed, stating that "the controls are very user-friendly and well explained".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *GameSpot*'s Greg Kasavin wrote that despite the game's improved graphics, "there's nothing foreign about its appearance" and that most game features will be "immediately recognizable if you've played a real-time strategy game before".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *PC Zone* agreed, but in a negative sense—it argued that *The Age of Kings* "is essentially an update of a two-year-old game".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Richards was surprised by the quality of *The Age of Kings*' graphics, considering they were all bitmapped.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] However, *AllGame* complained that units were sometimes difficult to tell apart, a point numerous reviewers agreed on.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It also considered the sound of *The Age of Kings* a negative, but not something significant enough to draw players away from the game's overall quality.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *IGN* stated that cutscenes were somewhat bland, but that overall the graphics added "an amazing amount of detail to the actual game".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Werner agreed: "the most noticeable graphical advancements", he wrote, were "the sheer size and scale of things".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *Game Revolution* stated "*AOE2* is the best looking of the 2D RTS games out there right now".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] A PlayStation 2 port was released by Konami in 2001 for Europe and in 2002 for Japan.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] A Nintendo DS spinoff, *Age of Empires: The Age of Kings* was released in 2006.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] An expansion for *The Age of Kings*, *The Conquerors*, was released in 2000.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It introduced numerous new game features, including unique technologies for each civilization, and five new civilizations.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Two of these, the Aztecs and the Mayans, represent the New World and have a distinctive architectural style.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Other new civilizations are the Huns, Koreans, and Spanish.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] In 2005, a mobile version of *Age of Empires II* was released for Java mobile devices (J2ME), called *Age of Empires II Mobile* and developed by In-Fusio.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It featured much simplified gameplay and graphics, designed for the mobile devices of the time.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The success of *Age of Empires II* also spurred the continuation of the franchise: the third historical game in the series, *Age of Empires III*, was released in 2005.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game portrayed the European colonization of the Americas.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Aside from one significant feature, the home city, the game's design was largely similar to that of its predecessor.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The multiplayer-only *Age of Empires Online* was released in 2012.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] While the game was freely accessible, it featured premium content which could either be earned through gameplay or purchased, enabling the player to use higher-tier equipment and new game modes.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Active development of the game ended on January 1, 2014, when executive producer Kevin Perry stated that adding new content was "no longer cost effective," and announced that the game would be moving from "development phase" to its "support phase".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game servers were subsequently shut down on July 1, 2014.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] In 2012, Hidden Path Entertainment began working on a high-definition remake of *Age of Empires II*, an effort spearheaded by Matt Pritchard, an original lead programmer at Ensemble Studios.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] On March 7, 2013, its release was announced, branded as *Age of Empires II: HD Edition*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It has improved graphics, widescreen support and new multiplayer options through Steam.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It was released on April 9, 2013, and there was a pre-order available on April 5.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *HD Edition* received mixed reviews, with aggregate review website Metacritic assigning a score of 68 out of 100 based on reviews from 20 critics.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Critics agreed that the *HD Edition* changed very little from the original game, though Steam Workshop integration was widely praised.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] Three official expansion packs were released for *HD Edition*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The first, *The Forgotten*, is based on a fan-made expansion, *The Forgotten Empires*.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The pack introduces five new civilizations: the Incas, Indians, Italians, Magyars, and Slavs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It includes new maps, campaigns (Alaric I, Bari, Dracula, El Dorado, Francesco I Sforza, and Prithviraj), units, a new game mode, an increase of the maximum population limit from 200 to 500, and numerous balance and gameplay adjustments.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The expansion pack was developed by the team that created the mod with the assistance of SkyBox Labs.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] A second expansion pack for *Age of Empires II HD*, *The African Kingdoms*, was released on November 5, 2015, and introduces four new civilizations: the Berbers, Ethiopians, Malians, and the Portuguese.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It includes new maps, campaigns (Tariq ibn Ziyad, Yodit, Sundjata, and Francisco de Almeida), as well as new units, new game modes including Capture the Relic and Treaty, and numerous balance and gameplay adjustments.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The third expansion pack, *Rise of the Rajas*, was released on December 19, 2016.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] On August 21, 2017, at Gamescom, Microsoft announced a remaster titled *Age of Empires II: Definitive Edition* was in development by Forgotten Empires, Tantalus Media, and Wicked Witch Software.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] On June 9, 2019, Microsoft revealed the gameplay trailer at Xbox E3 2019.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] The game includes all content from the previous editions and expansions, as well as new 4K graphics.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] It was released via Xbox Game Pass for PC, the Microsoft Store, and Steam on November 14, 2019.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-empires-ii] *Definitive Edition* has received multiple expansions.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The **Age of Sail** is the period in European history from the mid-15th or 16th century to, at the latest, the mid-19th century, in which the dominance of sailing ships in global trade and warfare culminated.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Marked by the introduction of naval artillery, the Age of Sail ultimately reached its highest extent at the advent of steam power.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Enabled by the advances of the related age of navigation, it is identified as a distinctive element of the early modern period and the Age of Discovery.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Like most periodic eras, defining the age is inexact and serves only as a general description.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The term is used differently for warships and merchant vessels.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] By the 14th century naval artillery was employed in Europe, documented at the Battle of Arnemuiden (1338).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The 15th century saw the Iberian naval ventures all the way along the African Atlantic coast and across the Atlantic Ocean, starting the Age of Discovery.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] For warships, the age of sail runs roughly from the Battle of Lepanto in 1571, the last significant engagement in which oar-propelled galleys played a major role, to the development of steam-powered warships.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The period between the mid-19th century to the early 20th century, when sailing vessels reached their peak of size and complexity (e.g. clippers and windjammers), is sometimes referred to as the "Golden Age of Sail".
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The second sea-going steamboat was Richard Wright's first steamboat *Experiment*, an ex-French lugger; she steamed from Leeds to Yarmouth in July 1813.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The first iron steamship to go to sea was the 116-ton *Aaron Manby*, built in 1821 by Aaron Manby at the Horseley Ironworks, and became the first iron-built vessel to put to sea when she crossed the English Channel in 1822, arriving in Paris on 22 June.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] She carried passengers and freight to Paris in 1822 at an average speed of 8 knots (9.2 mph; 15 km/h).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The first purpose-built steam battleship was the 90-gun *Napoléon* in 1850.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Multiple steam battleships saw action during the Crimean War, especially the Allied (British, French and Ottoman) fleet Bombardment of Sevastopol as part of the Siege of Sevastopol (1854–1855).
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The first ironclad battleship, *Gloire*, was launched by the French Navy in November 1859.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] In the March 1862 Battle of Hampton Roads, the ironclad CSS *Virginia* fought USS *Monitor*, making this the first fight between ironclads.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The Suez Canal in the Middle East, which opened in 1869, was more practical for steamships than for sailing ships, achieving a much shorter European-Asian sea route, which coincided with more fuel-efficient steamships, starting with *Agamemnon* in 1865.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] HMS *Devastation*, the first class of ocean-going battleships that did not carry sails, was commissioned in 1871.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships continued to be an economical way to transport bulk cargo on long voyages into the 1920s and 1930s, though steamships soon pushed them out of those trades as well.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing ships do not require fuel or complex engines to be powered; thus they tended to be more independent from sophisticated dedicated support bases on land.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Crucially though, steam-powered ships held a speed advantage and were rarely hindered by adverse winds, freeing steam-powered vessels from the necessity of following trade winds.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] As a result, cargo and supplies could reach a foreign port in a fraction of the time it took a sailing ship.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Sailing vessels were pushed into narrower and narrower economic niches and gradually disappeared from commercial trade.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] Today, sailing vessels are only economically viable for small-scale coastal fishing, along with recreational uses such as yachting and passenger sail excursion ships.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] In recent decades, the commercial shipping industry has been reviving interest in wind assisted ships as a way to conserve fuel in the interest of sustainability.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] A **New Age of Sail** has been predicted by some experts to occur by 2030, driven by a revolution in energy technology and a desire to reduce carbon emissions from maritime shipping through wind-assisted propulsion.
[src:borobudur-ship/age-of-sail] The book *Trade Winds: A Voyage to a Sustainable Future for Shipping* discusses the potential of a return to wind propulsion through the firsthand experiences of Christiaan De Beukelaer, who spent five months aboard a sailing cargo ship in 2020.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] The concept for *Alingano Maisu* came about in 2001 when two Hawaiian voyaging groups, the Polynesian Voyaging Society and Na Kalai Waʻa Moku o Hawaiʻi, met with Piailug.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] The two hulls of the 56-foot (17 m) vessel were fabricated by the Friends of *Hōkūleʻa* and *Hawaiʻiloa* on Oʻahu and shipped to the Island of Hawaiʻi where Na Kalai Waʻa completed construction of the canoe.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] The Polynesian Voyaging Society provided much of the funding for the voyaging aspect of the project as well as an escort boat to help sail the canoe to Satawal.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] The canoe is home-ported on the island of Yap under the command of Piailug's son, Sesario Sewralur.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] Accompanied by *Hōkūleʻa*, the *Maisu* left Kawaihae, Hawaii, on January 18, 2007.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] After stops in the Marshall Islands, Pohnpei, and Chuuk, the Maisu reached Satawal on March 15, 2007.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] On March 18, while on Satawal, five native Hawaiian navigators on the voyage were inducted into pwo, a sacred Micronesian brotherhood of master navigators.
[src:borobudur-ship/alingano-maisu] In June 2008, Palau Community College announced that there will be a one-year program in traditional non-instrumental navigation on the *Alingano Maisu* under Sesario Sewralur.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Well-known ancient artwork and sculptures, each representing a certain civilisation.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] The three-age system periodises ancient history into the Stone Age, the Bronze Age, and the Iron Age, with recorded history usually considered to begin with the Bronze Age.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] The start and end of the three ages vary between world regions.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] In many regions the Bronze Age is generally considered to begin a few centuries prior to 3000 BC, while the end of the Iron Age varies from the early first millennium BC in some regions to the late first millennium AD in others.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] During the time period of ancient history, the world population was exponentially increasing due to the Neolithic Revolution, which was in full progress.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] In 10,000 BC, the world population stood at an estimated 2 million, it rose to 45 million by 3000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] By the Iron Age in 1000 BC, the population had risen to 72 million.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] By the end of the ancient period in AD 500, the world population is thought to have stood at 209 million.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] In 10,500 years, the world population increased by 100 times.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Prehistory is the period before written history.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Most of the knowledge of that period comes from the work of archaeologists.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] The early human migrations in the Lower Paleolithic saw *Homo erectus* spread across Eurasia 1.8 million years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for the use of fire has been dated as early as 1.8 million years ago, a date which is contested, with generally accepted evidence for the controlled use of fire dating to 780,000 years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Actual use of hearths first appears 400,000 years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Dates for the emergence of *Homo sapiens* (modern humans) range from 250,000 to 160,000 years ago, with the varying dates being based on DNA studies and fossils respectively.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Some 50,000 years ago, *Homo sapiens* migrated out of Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] They reached Australia about 45,000 years ago, southwestern Europe about the same time, southeastern Europe and Siberia around 40,000 years ago, and Japan about 30,000 years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Humans migrated to the Americas about 15,000 years ago.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Evidence for agriculture emerges in about 9000 BC in what is now eastern Turkey and spread through the Fertile Crescent.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Settlement at Göbekli Tepe began around 9500 BC and may have the world's oldest temple.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] The Nile River Valley has evidence of sorghum and millet cultivation starting around 8000 BC and agricultural use of yams in Western Africa perhaps dates to the same time period.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Cultivation of millet, rice, and legumes began around 7000 BC in China.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Taro cultivation in New Guinea dates to about 7000 BC also with squash cultivation in Mesoamerica perhaps sharing that date.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Animal domestication began with the domestication of dogs, which dates to at least 15,000 years ago, and perhaps even earlier.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Sheep and goats were domesticated around 9000 BC in the Fertile Crescent, alongside the first evidence for agriculture.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Other animals, such as pigs and poultry, were later domesticated and used as food sources.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Cattle and water buffalo were domesticated around 7000 BC and horses, donkeys, and camels were domesticated by about 4000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] All of these animals were used not only for food, but to carry and pull people and loads, greatly increasing human ability to do work.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] The invention of the simple plough by 6000 BC further increased agricultural efficiency.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Metal use in the form of hammered copper items predates the discovery of smelting of copper ores, which happened around 6000 BC in western Asia and independently in eastern Asia before 2000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Gold and silver use dates to between 6000 and 5000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Alloy metallurgy began with bronze in about 3500 BC in Mesopotamia and was developed independently in China by 2000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Pottery developed independently throughout the world, with fired pots appearing first among the Jomon of Japan and in West Africa at Mali.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Sometime between 5000 and 4000 BC the potter's wheel was invented.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] By 3000 BC, the pottery wheel was adapted into wheeled vehicles which could be used to carry loads further and easier than with human or animal power alone.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Writing developed separately in five different locations in human history: Mesopotamia, Egypt, India, China, and Mesoamerica.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] By 3400 BC, "proto-literate" cuneiform spread in the Middle East.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Egypt developed its own system of hieroglyphs by about 3200 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] By 2800 BC the Indus Valley Civilisation had developed its Indus script, which remains undeciphered.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Chinese Characters were independently developed in China during the Shang dynasty in the form of the Oracle Bone Script dating to the period 1600 to 1100 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p01] Writing in Mesoamerica dates to 600 BC with the Zapotec civilization.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The ancient Near East is considered the cradle of civilisation.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It began the study of the stars and the sciences of astronomy and mathematics.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Mesopotamia is the site of some of the earliest known civilisations in the world.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Agricultural communities emerged in the area with the Halaf culture around 8000 BC and continued to expand through the Ubaid period around 6000 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Cities began in the Uruk period (4000–3100 BC) and expanded during the Jemdet Nasr (3100–2900 BC) and Early Dynastic (2900–2350 BC) periods.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The surplus of storable foodstuffs created by this economy allowed the population to settle in one place instead of migrating after crops and herds.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It also allowed for a much greater population density, and in turn required an extensive labour force and division of labour.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] This organisation led to the necessity of record keeping and the development of writing.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia was an Amorite state in lower Mesopotamia (modern southern Iraq), with Babylon as its capital.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Babylonia emerged when Hammurabi created an empire out of the territories of the former kingdoms of Sumer and Akkad.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire, or Chaldea, was Babylonia from the 7th and 6th centuries BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Under the reign of Nebuchadnezzar II, it conquered Jerusalem.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] This empire also created the Hanging Gardens of Babylon and the still-surviving Ishtar Gate as architectural embellishments of its capital at Babylon.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Akkad was a city and its surrounding region near Babylon.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Akkad also became the capital of the Akkadian Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Despite an extensive search, the precise site has never been found.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Akkad reached the height of its power between about 2330 and 2150 BC, following the conquests of King Sargon of Akkad.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Through the spread of Sargon's empire, the language of Akkad, known as Akkadian from the city, spread and replaced the Sumerian language in Mesopotamia and eventually by 1450 BC was the main language of diplomacy in the Near East.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Assyria was originally a region on the Upper Tigris, where a small state was created in the 19th century BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The capital was at Assur, which gave the state its name.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Later, as a nation and empire that came to control all of the Fertile Crescent, Egypt, and much of Anatolia, the term "Assyria proper" referred to roughly the northern half of Mesopotamia (the southern half being Babylonia), with Nineveh as its capital.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Assyrian kings controlled a large kingdom at three different times in history.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] These are called the *Old* (20th to 18th centuries BC), *Middle* (14th to 11th centuries BC), and *Neo-Assyrian* (9th to 7th centuries BC) kingdoms, or periods.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Mitanni was a Hurrian empire in northern Mesopotamia founded around 1500 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Mitanians conquered and controlled Assyria until the 14th century BC while contending with Egypt for control of parts of modern Syria.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Its capital was Washukanni, whose precise location has not been determined by archaeologists.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Medes and Persians were peoples who had appeared in the Iranian plateau around 1500 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Both peoples spoke Indo-European languages and were mostly pastoralists with a tradition of horse archery.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Medes established their own Median Empire by the 6th century BC, having defeated the Neo-Assyrian Empire with the Chaldeans in 614 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid Empire was founded by Cyrus the Great, who first became king of the Persians, then conquered the Medes, Lydia, and Babylon by 539 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The empire built on earlier Mesopotamian systems of government to govern their large empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] By building roads, they improved both the ability to send governmental instructions throughout their lands as well as improving the ability of their military forces to be deployed rapidly.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Increased trade and upgraded farming techniques increased wealth, but also exacerbated inequalities between social classes.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The empire's location at the centre of trading networks spread its intellectual and philosophical ideas throughout a wide area, and its religion, while not itself spreading far, had an impact on later religions such as Christianity, Islam, and Judaism.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Cyrus' son Cambyses II conquered Egypt, while a later emperor, Darius the Great, expanded the empire to the Indus River, creating the largest empire in the world to that date.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] But Darius and his son Xerxes I failed to expand into Greece, with expeditions in 490 and 480 BC eventually failing.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Achaemenid dynasty and empire fell to Alexander the Great by 330 BC, and after Alexander's death, much of the area previously ruled by the Cyrus and his successors was ruled by the Seleucid dynasty.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Parthia was an Iranian civilisation situated in the northeastern part of modern Iran.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Their power was based on a combination of military power based on heavy cavalry with a decentralised governing structure based on a federated system.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Parthian Empire was led by the Arsacid dynasty, which by around 155 BC under Mithradates I had mostly conquered the Seleucid Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Parthia had many wars with the Romans, but it was rebellions within the empire that ended it in the 3rd century AD.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Sasanian Empire began when the Parthian Empire ended in AD 224.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Their rulers claimed the Achaemenids as ancestors and set up their capital at Ctesiphon in Mesopotamia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Their period of greatest military expansion occurred under Shapur I, who by the time of his death in AD 272 had defeated Roman imperial armies and set up buffer states between the Sasanians and Roman Empires.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] After Shapur, the Sasanians were under more pressure from the Kushans to their east as well as the Roman then Byzantine Empire to its west.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] However, the Sasanians rebuilt and founded numerous cities and their merchants travelled widely and introduced crops such as sugar, rice, and cotton into the Iranian plateau.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] But in AD 651, the last Sassanid emperor was killed by the expanding Islamic Arabs.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites first came to Anatolia about 1900 BC and during the period 1600–1500 they expanded into Mesopotamia where they adopted the cuneiform script to their Indo-European language.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] By 1200 their empire stretched to Phoenicia and eastern Anatolia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] They improved two earlier technologies from Mesopotamia and spread these new techniques widely – improved iron working and light chariots with spoked wheels in warfare.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Hittites introduced the casting of iron with molds and then hammering it which enabled weapons and tools to be made stronger and also cheaper.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Although chariots had been used previously, the use of spoked wheels allowed the chariots to be much lighter and more maneuverable.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] In 1274 BC the Hittites clashed with the Egyptians at the Battle of Kadesh, where both sides claimed victory.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] In 1207 BC the Hittite capital of Hattusa was sacked, ending the Hittite Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Israel and Judah were related Iron Age kingdoms of the ancient Levant and had existed during the Iron Ages and the Neo-Babylonian, Persian and Hellenistic periods.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The name Israel first appears in the stele of the Egyptian pharaoh Merneptah around 1209 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] This "Israel" was a cultural and probably political entity of the central highlands, well enough established to be perceived by the Egyptians as a possible challenge to their hegemony, but an ethnic group rather than an organised state.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Israel had emerged by the middle of the 9th century BC, when the Assyrian King Shalmaneser III named "Ahab the Israelite" among his enemies at the battle of Qarqar (853).
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Judah emerged somewhat later than Israel, probably during the 9th century BC, but the subject is one of considerable controversy.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Israel came into conflict with the Assyrians, who conquered Israel in 722 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Neo-Babylonian Empire did the same to Judah in 586.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] After both conquests, the conquering forces deported many of the inhabitants to other regions of their respective empires.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Phoenicia was an ancient civilisation centred in the north of ancient Canaan, with its heartland along the coastal regions of modern-day Lebanon, Syria and Israel.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Phoenician civilisation was an enterprising maritime trading culture that spread across the Mediterranean between the period of 1550 to 300 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] One Phoenician colony, Carthage, ruled an empire in the Western Mediterranean until being defeated by Rome in the Punic Wars.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Phoenicians invented the Phoenician alphabet, the forerunner of the modern alphabet still in use today.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The history of Pre-Islamic Arabia before the rise of Islam in the AD 630s is not known in great detail.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Archaeological exploration in the Arabian Peninsula has been sparse; indigenous written sources are limited to the many inscriptions and coins from southern Arabia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Existing material consists primarily of written sources from other traditions (such as Egyptians, Greeks, Persians, Romans, etc.) and oral traditions later recorded by Islamic scholars.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] A number of small kingdoms existed in Arabia from around AD 100 to perhaps about AD 400.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt was a long-lived civilisation geographically located in north-eastern Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It was concentrated along the middle to lower reaches of the Nile River, reaching its greatest extent during the 2nd millennium BC, which is referred to as the New Kingdom period.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It reached broadly from the Nile Delta in the north, as far south as Jebel Barkal at the Fourth Cataract of the Nile.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Extensions to the geographical range of ancient Egyptian civilisation included, at different times, areas of the southern Levant, the Eastern Desert and the Red Sea coastline, the Sinai Peninsula, and the Western Desert (focused on the several oases).
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egypt developed over at least three and a half millennia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It began with the incipient unification of Nile Valley polities around 3100 BC, traditionally under Menes.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Overseeing these activities were a socio-political and economic elite under the figure of a (semi)-divine ruler from a succession of ruling dynasties.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Egyptian history is divided across various periods, beginning with the Old Kingdom, which saw pyramid building on a large scale.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] After 2100 BC, the Old Kingdom dissolved into smaller states during the First Intermediate Period, which lasted about 100 years.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom began around 2000 BC with the reunification of Egypt under pharoes ruling from Thebes.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Middle Kingdom ended with the conquest of northern Egypt by the Hyksos around 1650 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Hyksos were expelled from Egypt and the land was reunited in the New Kingdom around 1550 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] This period lasted until about 1000 BC, and saw Egypt expand its borders into Palestine and Syria.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Third Intermediate Period was marked by the rule of priests as well as the conquest of Egypt by Nubian kings and then later Assyria, Persia, and Macedonians.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Carthage was founded around 814 BC by Phoenician settlers.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Ancient Carthage was a city-state that ruled an empire through alliances and trade influence that stretched throughout North Africa and modern Spain.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] At the height of the city's influence, its empire included most of the western Mediterranean.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The empire was in a constant state of struggle with the Roman Republic, which led to a series of conflicts known as the Punic Wars.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] After the third and final Punic War, Carthage was destroyed and then occupied by Roman forces.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Nearly all of the territory held by Carthage fell into Roman hands.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Ta-Seti kingdom in Nubia to the south of Egypt was conquered by Egyptian rulers around 3100 BC, but by 2500 BC the Nubians had created a new kingdom further south, known as the Kingdom of Kush, centred on the upper Nile with a capital at Kerma.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] In the Egyptian New Kingdom period, Kush once more was conquered by Egypt.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] However, by 1100 BC a new kingdom of Kush had formed, with a capital at Napata.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Nubian rulers conquered Egypt around 760 BC and retained control for about a century.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum was an important trading nation in northeastern Africa centred in present-day Eritrea and northern Ethiopia, it existed from approximately AD 100 to 940, growing from the Iron Age proto-Aksumite period around the 4th century BC to achieve prominence by the 1st century AD.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Kingdom of Aksum at its height by the early 6th-century AD extended through much of modern Ethiopia and across the Red Sea to Arabia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The capital city of the empire was Aksum, now in northern Ethiopia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Nok culture appeared in Nigeria around 1000 BC and mysteriously vanished around AD 200.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation's social system is thought to have been highly advanced.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Nok civilisation was considered to be the earliest sub-Saharan producer of life-sized Terracotta which have been discovered by archaeologists.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The Nok also used iron smelting that may have been independently developed.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The civilisation of Djenné-Djenno was located in the Niger River Valley in the country of Mali and is considered to be among the oldest urbanised centres and the best-known archaeology site in sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] This archaeological site is located about 3 kilometers (1.9 miles) away from the modern town and is believed to have been involved in long-distance trade and possibly the domestication of African rice.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The site is believed to exceed 33 hectares (82 acres); however, this is yet to be confirmed with extensive survey work.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] With the help of archaeological excavations mainly by Susan and Roderick McIntosh, the site is known to have been occupied from 250 BC to AD 900.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The city is believed to have been abandoned and moved where the current city is located due to the spread of Islam and the building of the Great Mosque of Djenné.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Previously, it was assumed that advanced trade networks and complex societies did not exist in the region until the arrival of traders from Southwest Asia.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] However, sites such as Djenné-Djenno disprove this, as these traditions in West Africa flourished long before.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Towns similar to that at Djenne-Jeno also developed at the site of Dia, also in Mali along the Niger River, from around 900 BC.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Dhar Tichitt and Oualata were prominent among the early urban centres, dated to 2000 BC, in present-day Mauritania.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] About 500 stone settlements littered the region in the former savannah of the Sahara.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] It has been found that the Soninke of the Mandé peoples were responsible for constructing such settlements.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Around 300 BC, the region became more desiccated and the settlements began to decline, most likely relocating to Koumbi Saleh.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] From the type of architecture and pottery, it is believed that Tichit was related to the subsequent Ghana Empire.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Old Jenne (Djenne) began to be settled around 300 BC, producing iron and with sizeable population, evidenced in crowded cemeteries.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] The inhabitants and creators of these settlements during these periods are thought to have been ancestors of the Soninke people.
[src:borobudur-ship/ancient-history-p02] Peoples speaking precursors to the modern-day Bantu languages began to spread throughout southern Africa, and by 2000 BC they were expanding past the Congo River and into the Great Lakes area.
